# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: graphene-materials
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:graphene-materials/fullerene] A **fullerene** is a molecule composed solely of 3-coordinate carbon.
[src:graphene-materials/fullerene] The carbons are usually in the form of 5- and 6-membered rings.
[src:graphene-materials/fullerene] The family is named after buckminsterfullerene (C60), which in turn is named after Buckminster Fuller.
[src:graphene-materials/fullerene] C60 is also the first discovered and best characterized fullerene.
[src:graphene-materials/fullerene] C60 has a hollow sphere-like form, but other fullerenes are known with ellipsoid-like shapes.
[src:graphene-materials/fullerene] The closed fullerenes, especially C60, are also informally called **buckyballs** for their resemblance to the standard ball of association football.
[src:graphene-materials/fullerene] The icosahedral C 60H 60 cage was mentioned in 1965 as a possible topological structure.
[src:graphene-materials/fullerene] Eiji Osawa predicted the existence of C 60 in 1970.
[src:graphene-materials/fullerene] He noticed that the structure of a corannulene molecule was a subset of the shape of a football, and hypothesised that a full ball shape could also exist.
[src:graphene-materials/fullerene] Japanese scientific journals reported his idea, but neither it nor any translations of it reached Europe or the Americas.
[src:graphene-materials/fullerene] Henson (former member of the UK Atomic Energy Research Establishment) proposed the C 60 structure and made a model of it.
[src:graphene-materials/fullerene] Unfortunately, the evidence for that new form of carbon was very weak at the time, so the proposal was met with skepticism, and was never published.
[src:graphene-materials/fullerene] Galpern made a quantum-chemical analysis of the stability of C 60 and calculated its electronic structure.
[src:graphene-materials/fullerene] The paper was published in 1973, but the scientific community did not give much importance to this theoretical prediction.
[src:graphene-materials/fullerene] Around 1980, Sumio Iijima identified the molecule of C 60 from an electron microscope image of carbon black, where it formed the core of a particle with the structure of a "bucky onion".
[src:graphene-materials/fullerene] Also in the 1980s at MIT, Mildred Dresselhaus and Morinobu Endo, collaborating with T.
[src:graphene-materials/fullerene] Fullerenes had been predicted for some time, but only after their accidental synthesis in 1985 were they detected in nature and outer space.
[src:graphene-materials/fullerene] The discovery of fullerenes greatly expanded the number of known allotropes of carbon, which had previously been limited to graphite, diamond, and amorphous carbon such as soot and charcoal.
[src:graphene-materials/fullerene] They have been the subject of intense research, both for their chemistry and for their technological applications, especially in materials science, electronics, and nanotechnology.
[src:graphene-materials/fullerene] In 1985, Harold Kroto of the University of Sussex, working with James R.
[src:graphene-materials/fullerene] Heath, Sean O'Brien, Robert Curl and Richard Smalley from Rice University, discovered fullerenes in the sooty residue created by vaporising carbon in a helium atmosphere.
[src:graphene-materials/fullerene] In the mass spectrum of the product, discrete peaks appeared corresponding to molecules with the exact mass of sixty or seventy or more carbon atoms, namely C 60 and C 70.
[src:graphene-materials/fullerene] The team identified their structure as the now familiar "buckyballs".
[src:graphene-materials/fullerene] The "ene" ending was chosen to indicate that the carbons are unsaturated, being connected to only three other atoms instead of the normal four.
[src:graphene-materials/fullerene] The shortened name "fullerene" eventually came to be applied to the whole family.
[src:graphene-materials/fullerene] Kroto, Curl, and Smalley were awarded the 1996 Nobel Prize in Chemistry for their roles in the discovery of this class of molecules.
[src:graphene-materials/fullerene] Kroto and the Rice team already discovered other fullerenes besides C60, and the list was much expanded in the following years.
[src:graphene-materials/fullerene] Carbon nanotubes were first discovered and synthesized in 1991.
[src:graphene-materials/fullerene] After their discovery, minute quantities of fullerenes were found to be produced in sooty flames, and by lightning discharges in the atmosphere.
[src:graphene-materials/fullerene] In 1992, fullerenes were found in a family of mineraloids known as shungites in Karelia, Russia.
[src:graphene-materials/fullerene] The production techniques were improved by many scientists, including Donald Huffman, Wolfgang Krätschmer, Lowell D.
[src:graphene-materials/fullerene] Thanks to their efforts, by 1990 it was relatively easy to produce gram-sized samples of fullerene powder.
[src:graphene-materials/fullerene] Fullerene purification remains a challenge to chemists and to a large extent determines fullerene prices.
[src:graphene-materials/fullerene] In 2010, the spectral signatures of C60 and C70 were observed by NASA's Spitzer infrared telescope in a cloud of cosmic dust surrounding a star 6500 light years away.
[src:graphene-materials/fullerene] Below is a table of main closed carbon fullerenes synthesized and characterized so far, with their CAS number when known.
[src:graphene-materials/fullerene] Fullerenes with fewer than 60 carbon atoms have been called "lower fullerenes", and those with more than 70 atoms "higher fullerenes".
[src:graphene-materials/fullerene] In the table, "Num.Isom." is the number of possible isomers within the "isolated pentagon rule", which states that two pentagons in a fullerene should not share edges.
[src:graphene-materials/fullerene] "Mol.Symm." is the symmetry of the molecule, whereas "Cryst.Symm." is that of the crystalline framework in the solid state.
[src:graphene-materials/fullerene] Both are specified for the most experimentally abundant form(s).
[src:graphene-materials/fullerene] The asterisk * marks symmetries with more than one chiral form.
[src:graphene-materials/fullerene] The smallest possible fullerene is the dodecahedral C 20.
[src:graphene-materials/fullerene] There are no fullerenes with 22 vertices.
[src:graphene-materials/fullerene] The number of different fullerenes C2n grows with increasing *n* = 12, 13, 14, ..., roughly in proportion to *n*9 (sequence A007894 in the OEIS).
[src:graphene-materials/fullerene] For instance, there are 1812 non-isomorphic fullerenes C 60.
[src:graphene-materials/fullerene] Note that only one form of C 60, buckminsterfullerene, has no pair of adjacent pentagons (the smallest such fullerene).
[src:graphene-materials/fullerene] To further illustrate the growth, there are 214,127,713 non-isomorphic fullerenes C 200, 15,655,672 of which have no adjacent pentagons.
[src:graphene-materials/fullerene] Optimized structures of many fullerene isomers are published and listed on the web.
[src:graphene-materials/fullerene] When C 76 or C 82 crystals are grown from toluene solution they have a monoclinic symmetry.
[src:graphene-materials/fullerene] The crystal structure contains toluene molecules packed between the spheres of the fullerene.
[src:graphene-materials/fullerene] However, evaporation of the solvent from C 76 transforms it into a face-centered cubic form.
[src:graphene-materials/fullerene] Both monoclinic and face-centered cubic (fcc) phases are known for better-characterized C 60 and C 70 fullerenes.
[src:graphene-materials/fullerene] Buckminsterfullerene is the smallest fullerene molecule containing pentagonal and hexagonal rings in which no two pentagons share an edge (which can be destabilizing, as in pentalene).
[src:graphene-materials/fullerene] It is also most common in terms of natural occurrence, as it can often be found in soot.
[src:graphene-materials/fullerene] The empirical formula of buckminsterfullerene is C 60 and its structure is a truncated icosahedron, which resembles an association football ball of the type made of twenty hexagons and twelve pentagons, with a carbon atom at the vertices of each polygon and a bond along each polygon edge.
[src:graphene-materials/fullerene] The van der Waals diameter of a buckminsterfullerene molecule is about 1.1 nanometers (nm).
[src:graphene-materials/fullerene] The nucleus to nucleus diameter of a buckminsterfullerene molecule is about 0.71 nm.
[src:graphene-materials/fullerene] The buckminsterfullerene molecule has two bond lengths.
[src:graphene-materials/fullerene] The 6:6 ring bonds (between two hexagons) can be considered "double bonds" and are shorter (1.401 Å) than the 6:5 bonds (1.458 Å, between a hexagon and a pentagon).
[src:graphene-materials/fullerene] The weighted average bond length is 1.44 Å.
[src:graphene-materials/fullerene] Another fairly common fullerene has empirical formula C 70, but fullerenes with 72, 76, 84 and even up to 100 carbon atoms are commonly obtained.
[src:graphene-materials/fullerene] C 76, C 78, C 80, and C 84 are chiral because they are D2-symmetric.
[src:graphene-materials/fullerene] Many heterofullerenes have been synthesized (or studied theoretically) in which some or all the carbon atoms are replaced by other elements, such as nitrogen (azafullerenes).
[src:graphene-materials/fullerene] Buckyballs containing boron atoms (borafullerenes) have been observed, such as C40 and C80.
[src:graphene-materials/fullerene] Inorganic (carbon-free) fullerene-type structures have been built with the molybdenum(IV) sulfide (MoS2), long used as a graphite-like lubricant, tungsten (WS2), titanium (TiS2) and niobium (NbS2).
[src:graphene-materials/fullerene] These materials were found to be stable up to at least 350 tons/cm2 (34.3 GPa).
[src:graphene-materials/fullerene] Icosahedral or distorted-icosahedral fullerene-like complexes have also been prepared for germanium, tin, and lead; some of these complexes are spacious enough to hold most transition metal atoms.
[src:graphene-materials/fullerene] Carbon nanotubes are described as open-ended cylinders are a major variant of fullerenes and have received much attention.
[src:graphene-materials/fullerene] These tubes of carbon are usually only a few nanometres wide, but they can range from less than a micrometer to several millimeters in length.
[src:graphene-materials/fullerene] They often have closed ends, but can be open-ended.
[src:graphene-materials/fullerene] There are also cases in which the tube reduces in diameter before closing off.
[src:graphene-materials/fullerene] Nested closed fullerenes have been named **bucky onions**, which have been proposed for use in lubricants.
[src:graphene-materials/fullerene] Nested carbon nanotubes, dubbed "carbon megatubes", have also been synthesized.
[src:graphene-materials/fullerene] The bulk solid form of pure or mixed fullerenes is called **fullerite**.
[src:graphene-materials/fullerene] Buckyballs can be connected, such as in linked "ball-and-chain" dimers (two buckyballs linked by a carbon chain) and rings of buckyballs linked together.
[src:graphene-materials/fullerene] Non-carbon nanotubes have attracted attention.
[src:graphene-materials/fullerene] Schlegel diagrams are often used to clarify the 3D structure of closed-shell fullerenes, as 2D projections are often not ideal in this sense.
[src:graphene-materials/fullerene] The Schlegel diagram is a projection of that skeleton onto one of the faces of the polyhedron, through a point just outside that face; so that all other vertices project inside that face.
[src:graphene-materials/fullerene] The Schlegel diagram of a closed fullerene is a graph that is planar and 3-regular (or "cubic"; meaning that all vertices have degree 3).
[src:graphene-materials/fullerene] A closed fullerene with sphere-like shell must have at least some cycles that are pentagons or heptagons.
[src:graphene-materials/fullerene] More precisely, if all the faces have 5 or 6 sides, it follows from Euler's polyhedron formula, *V*−*E*+*F*=2 (where *V*, *E*, *F* are the numbers of vertices, edges, and faces), that *V* must be even, and that there must be exactly 12 pentagons and *V*/2−10 hexagons.
[src:graphene-materials/fullerene] Similar constraints exist if the fullerene has heptagonal (seven-atom) cycles.
[src:graphene-materials/fullerene] Since each carbon atom is connected to only three neighbors, instead of the usual four, it is customary to describe those bonds as being a mixture of single and double covalent bonds.
[src:graphene-materials/fullerene] The hybridization of carbon in C60 has been reported to be sp2.01.
[src:graphene-materials/fullerene] The bonding state can be analyzed by Raman spectroscopy, IR spectroscopy and X-ray photoelectron spectroscopy.
[src:graphene-materials/fullerene] Additional atoms, ions, clusters, or small molecules can be trapped inside fullerenes to form inclusion compounds known as endohedral fullerenes.
[src:graphene-materials/fullerene] An unusual example is the egg-shaped fullerene Tb3N@C 84, which violates the isolated pentagon rule.
[src:graphene-materials/fullerene] Evidence for a meteor impact at the end of the Permian period was found by analyzing noble gases preserved by being trapped in fullerenes.
[src:graphene-materials/fullerene] Researchers have been able to increase the reactivity of fullerenes by attaching active groups to their surfaces.
[src:graphene-materials/fullerene] Buckminsterfullerene does not exhibit "superaromaticity": that is, the electrons in the hexagonal rings do not delocalize over the whole molecule.
[src:graphene-materials/fullerene] A spherical fullerene of *n* carbon atoms has *n* pi-bonding electrons, free to delocalize.
[src:graphene-materials/fullerene] These should try to delocalize over the whole molecule.
[src:graphene-materials/fullerene] The quantum mechanics of such an arrangement should be like only one shell of the well-known quantum mechanical structure of a single atom, with a stable filled shell for *n* = 2, 8, 18, 32, 50, 72, 98, 128, etc.
[src:graphene-materials/fullerene] (i.e., twice a perfect square number), but this series does not include 60.
[src:graphene-materials/fullerene] This 2(*N* + 1)2 rule (with *N* integer) for spherical aromaticity is the three-dimensional analogue of Hückel's rule.
[src:graphene-materials/fullerene] The 10+ cation would satisfy this rule, and should be aromatic.
[src:graphene-materials/fullerene] This has been shown to be the case using quantum chemical modelling, which showed the existence of strong diamagnetic sphere currents in the cation.
[src:graphene-materials/fullerene] As a result, C 60 in water tends to pick up two more electrons and become an anion.
[src:graphene-materials/fullerene] The *n*C 60 described below may be the result of C 60 trying to form a loose metallic bond.
[src:graphene-materials/fullerene] Under high pressure and temperature, buckyballs collapse to form various one-, two-, or three-dimensional carbon frameworks.
[src:graphene-materials/fullerene] Single-strand polymers are formed using the Atom Transfer Radical Addition Polymerization (ATRAP) route.
[src:graphene-materials/fullerene] "Ultrahard fullerite" is a coined term frequently used to describe material produced by high-pressure high-temperature (HPHT) processing of fullerite.
[src:graphene-materials/fullerene] Such treatment converts fullerite into a nanocrystalline form of diamond which has been reported to exhibit remarkable mechanical properties.
[src:graphene-materials/fullerene] Fullerenes are stable, but not totally unreactive.
[src:graphene-materials/fullerene] The sp2-hybridized carbon atoms, which are at their energy minimum in planar graphite, must be bent to form the closed sphere or tube, which produces angle strain.
[src:graphene-materials/fullerene] The characteristic reaction of fullerenes is electrophilic addition at 6,6-double bonds, which reduces angle strain by changing sp2-hybridized carbons into sp3-hybridized ones.
[src:graphene-materials/fullerene] The change in hybridized orbitals causes the bond angles to decrease from about 120° in the sp2 orbitals to about 109.5° in the sp3 orbitals.
[src:graphene-materials/fullerene] This decrease in bond angles allows for the bonds to bend less when closing the sphere or tube, and thus, the molecule becomes more stable.
[src:graphene-materials/fullerene] Fullerenes are soluble in many organic solvents, such as toluene, chlorobenzene, and 1,2,3-trichloropropane.
[src:graphene-materials/fullerene] Solubilities are generally rather low, such as 8 g/L for C60 in carbon disulfide.
[src:graphene-materials/fullerene] Still, fullerenes are the only known allotrope of carbon that can be dissolved in common solvents at room temperature.
[src:graphene-materials/fullerene] Among the best solvents is 1-chloronaphthalene, which will dissolve 51 g/L of C60.
[src:graphene-materials/fullerene] Solutions of pure buckminsterfullerene have a deep purple color.
[src:graphene-materials/fullerene] The higher fullerenes C 76 to C 84 have a variety of colors.
[src:graphene-materials/fullerene] Millimeter-sized crystals of C 60 and C 70, both pure and solvated, can be grown from benzene solution.
[src:graphene-materials/fullerene] Crystallization of C 60 from benzene solution below 30 °C (when solubility is maximum) yields a triclinic solid solvate C 60·4C 6H 6.
[src:graphene-materials/fullerene] Above 30 °C one obtains solvate-free fcc C 60.
[src:graphene-materials/fullerene] In 1999, researchers from the University of Vienna demonstrated that wave-particle duality applied to molecules such as fullerene.
[src:graphene-materials/fullerene] At the time, C60 was at least an order of magnitude more massive than any object whose wave properties had previously been observed, making the fullerene experiment a landmark demonstration that quantum interference persists at the macromolecular scale.
[src:graphene-materials/fullerene] Fullerenes are normally electrical insulators, but when crystallized with alkali metals, the resultant compound can be conducting or even superconducting.
[src:graphene-materials/fullerene] Two theories have been proposed to describe the molecular mechanisms that make fullerenes.
[src:graphene-materials/fullerene] The older, "bottom-up" theory proposes that they are built atom-by-atom.
[src:graphene-materials/fullerene] The alternative "top-down" approach claims that fullerenes form when much larger structures break into constituent parts.
[src:graphene-materials/fullerene] In 2013 researchers discovered that asymmetrical fullerenes formed from larger structures settle into stable fullerenes.
[src:graphene-materials/fullerene] The synthesized substance was a particular metallofullerene consisting of 84 carbon atoms with two additional carbon atoms and two yttrium atoms inside the cage.
[src:graphene-materials/fullerene] The process produced approximately 100 micrograms.
[src:graphene-materials/fullerene] However, they found that the asymmetrical molecule could theoretically collapse to form nearly every known fullerene and metallofullerene.
[src:graphene-materials/fullerene] Minor perturbations involving the breaking of a few molecular bonds cause the cage to become highly symmetrical and stable.
[src:graphene-materials/fullerene] This insight supports the theory that fullerenes can be formed from graphene when the appropriate molecular bonds are severed.
[src:graphene-materials/fullerene] According to the IUPAC, to name a fullerene, one must cite the number of member atoms for the rings which comprise the fullerene, its symmetry point group in the Schoenflies notation, and the total number of atoms.
[src:graphene-materials/fullerene] For example, buckminsterfullerene C60 is systematically named (C 60-*I*h)[5,6]fullerene.
[src:graphene-materials/fullerene] The name of the point group should be retained in any derivative of said fullerene, even if that symmetry is lost by the derivation.
[src:graphene-materials/fullerene] To indicate the position of substituted or attached elements, the fullerene atoms are usually numbered in a spiral path, usually starting with the ring on one of the main axes.
[src:graphene-materials/fullerene] If the structure of the fullerene does not allow such numbering, another starting atom was chosen to still achieve a spiral path sequence.
[src:graphene-materials/fullerene] The latter is the case for C70, which is (C 70-*D*5h(6))[5,6]fullerene in IUPAC notation.
[src:graphene-materials/fullerene] The symmetry *D*5h(6) means that this is the isomer where the *C*5 axis goes through a pentagon surrounded by hexagons rather than pentagons.
[src:graphene-materials/fullerene] In IUPAC's nomenclature, fully saturated analogues of fullerenes are called *fulleranes*.
[src:graphene-materials/fullerene] If the mesh has other element(s) substituted for one or more carbons, the compound is named a *heterofullerene*.
[src:graphene-materials/fullerene] If a double bond is replaced by a methylene bridge −CH2−, the resulting structure is a *homofullerene*.
[src:graphene-materials/fullerene] If an atom is fully deleted and missing valences saturated with hydrogen atoms, it is a *norfullerene*.
[src:graphene-materials/fullerene] When bonds are removed (both sigma and pi), the compound becomes *secofullerene*; if some new bonds are added in an unconventional order, it is a *cyclofullerene*.
[src:graphene-materials/fullerene] Fullerenes are components of soot which is produced in particular ways.
[src:graphene-materials/fullerene] In the original (and still prevailing) method, a large electric current is passed between two nearby graphite electrodes in an inert atmosphere.
[src:graphene-materials/fullerene] The resulting electric arc vaporizes the carbon that condenses into a sooty residue.
[src:graphene-materials/fullerene] Alternatively, soot is produced by laser ablation of graphite or pyrolysis of aromatic hydrocarbons.
[src:graphene-materials/fullerene] Combustion of benzene can also be efficient.
[src:graphene-materials/fullerene] These processes yield a mixture of various fullerenes and other forms of carbon.
[src:graphene-materials/fullerene] The fullerenes are then extracted from the soot using appropriate organic solvents and separated by chromatography.
[src:graphene-materials/fullerene] One can obtain milligram quantities of fullerenes with 80 atoms or more.
[src:graphene-materials/fullerene] C76, C78 and C84 are available commercially.
[src:graphene-materials/fullerene] Functionalized fullerenes have been researched extensively for several potential biomedical applications including high-performance MRI contrast agents, X-ray imaging contrast agents, photodynamic therapy for tumor treatment, and drug and gene delivery.
[src:graphene-materials/fullerene] Fullerene has been demonstrated in polymer-fullerene bulk heterojunction solar cells.
[src:graphene-materials/fullerene] This technology has been displaced by related non-fullerene devices.
[src:graphene-materials/fullerene] In 2013, a comprehensive review on the toxicity of fullerene was published reviewing work beginning in the early 1990s to present and concluded that very little evidence gathered since the discovery of fullerenes indicate that C 60 is toxic.
[src:graphene-materials/fullerene] It was recommended to assess the pharmacology of every new fullerene- or metallofullerene-based complex individually as a different compound.
[src:graphene-materials/fullerene] Examples of fullerenes appear frequently in popular culture.
[src:graphene-materials/fullerene] Fullerenes appeared in fiction well before scientists took serious interest in them.
[src:graphene-materials/fullerene] In a humorously speculative 1966 column for *New Scientist*, David Jones suggested the possibility of making giant hollow carbon molecules by distorting a plane hexagonal net with the addition of impurity atoms.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-nanoribbon] Large quantities of width-controlled GNRs can be produced via graphite nanotomy, where applying a sharp diamond knife on graphite produces graphite nanoblocks, which can then be exfoliated to produce GNRs as shown by Vikas Berry.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-nanoribbon] GNRs can also be produced by "unzipping" or axially cutting nanotubes.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-nanoribbon] In one such method multi-walled carbon nanotubes were unzipped in solution by action of potassium permanganate and sulfuric acid.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-nanoribbon] In another method GNRs were produced by plasma etching of nanotubes partly embedded in a polymer film.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-nanoribbon] More recently, graphene nanoribbons were grown onto silicon carbide (SiC) substrates using ion implantation followed by vacuum or laser annealing.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-nanoribbon] The latter technique allows any pattern to be written on SiC substrates with 5 nm precision.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-nanoribbon] GNRs were grown on the edges of three-dimensional structures etched into silicon carbide wafers.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-nanoribbon] When the wafers are heated to approximately 1,000 °C (1,270 K; 1,830 °F), silicon is preferentially driven off along the edges, forming nanoribbons whose structure is determined by the pattern of the three-dimensional surface.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-nanoribbon] The ribbons had perfectly smooth edges, annealed by the fabrication process.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-nanoribbon] Electron mobility measurements surpassing one million correspond to a sheet resistance of one ohm per square — two orders of magnitude lower than in two-dimensional graphene.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-nanoribbon] Nanoribbons narrower than 10 nm grown on a germanium wafer act like semiconductors, exhibiting a band gap.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-nanoribbon] Inside a reaction chamber, using chemical vapor deposition, methane is used to deposit hydrocarbons on the wafer surface, where they react with each other to produce long, smooth-edged ribbons.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-nanoribbon] The ribbons were used to create prototype transistors.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-nanoribbon] At a very slow growth rate, the graphene crystals naturally grow into long nanoribbons on a specific germanium crystal facet.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-nanoribbon] By controlling the growth rate and growth time, the researchers achieved control over the nanoribbon width.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-nanoribbon] Recently, researchers from SIMIT (Shanghai Institute of Microsystem and Information Technology, Chinese Academy of Sciences) reported on a strategy to grow graphene nanoribbons with controlled widths and smooth edges directly onto dielectric hexagonal boron nitride (h-BN) substrates.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-nanoribbon] The team use nickel nanoparticles to etch monolayer-deep, nanometre-wide trenches into h-BN, and subsequently fill them with graphene using chemical vapour deposition.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-nanoribbon] Modifying the etching parameters allows the width of the trench to be tuned to less than 10 nm, and the resulting sub-10-nm ribbons display bandgaps of almost 0.5 eV.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-nanoribbon] Integrating these nanoribbons into field effect transistor devices reveals on–off ratios of greater than 104 at room temperature, as well as high carrier mobilities of ~750 cm2 V−1 s−1.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-nanoribbon] In 2017 dry contact transfer was used to press a fiberglass applicator coated with a powder of atomically precise graphene nanoribbons on a hydrogen-passivated Si(100) surface under vacuum.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-nanoribbon] 80 of 115 GNRs visibly obscured the substrate lattice with an average apparent height of 0.30 nm.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-nanoribbon] The GNRs do not align to the Si lattice, indicating a weak coupling.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-nanoribbon] The average bandgap over 21 GNRs was 2.85 eV with a standard deviation of 0.13 eV.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-nanoribbon] The method unintentionally overlapped some nanoribbons, allowing the study of multilayer GNRs.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-nanoribbon] Such overlaps could be formed deliberately by manipulation with a scanning tunneling microscope.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-nanoribbon] Hydrogen depassivation left no band-gap.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-nanoribbon] Covalent bonds between the Si surface and the GNR leads to metallic behavior.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-nanoribbon] The Si surface atoms move outward, and the GNR changes from flat to distorted, with some C atoms moving in toward the Si surface.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-nanoribbon] The electronic states of GNRs largely depend on the edge structures (armchair or zigzag).
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-nanoribbon] In zigzag edges each successive edge segment is at the opposite angle to the previous.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-nanoribbon] In armchair edges, each pair of segments is a 120/-120 degree rotation of the prior pair.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-nanoribbon] The animation below provides a visualization explanation of both.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-nanoribbon] Zigzag edges provide the edge localized state with non-bonding molecular orbitals near the Fermi energy.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-nanoribbon] They are expected to have large changes in optical and electronic properties from quantization.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-nanoribbon] Calculations based on tight binding theory predict that zigzag GNRs are always metallic while armchairs can be either metallic or semiconducting, depending on their width.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-nanoribbon] However, density functional theory (DFT) calculations show that armchair nanoribbons are semiconducting with an energy gap scaling with the inverse of the GNR width.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-nanoribbon] Experiments verified that energy gaps increase with decreasing GNR width.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-nanoribbon] Graphene nanoribbons with controlled edge orientation have been fabricated by scanning tunneling microscope (STM) lithography.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-nanoribbon] Energy gaps up to 0.5 eV in a 2.5 nm wide armchair ribbon were reported.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-nanoribbon] Armchair nanoribbons are metallic or semiconducting and present spin polarized edges.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-nanoribbon] Their gap opens thanks to an unusual antiferromagnetic coupling between the magnetic moments at opposite edge carbon atoms.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-nanoribbon] This gap size is inversely proportional to the ribbon width and its behavior can be traced back to the spatial distribution properties of edge-state wave functions, and the mostly local character of the exchange interaction that originates the spin polarization.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-nanoribbon] Therefore, the quantum confinement, inter-edge superexchange, and intra-edge direct exchange interactions in zigzag GNR are important for its magnetism and band gap.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-nanoribbon] The edge magnetic moment and band gap of zigzag GNR are reversely proportional to the electron/hole concentration and they can be controlled by alkaline adatoms.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-nanoribbon] Their 2D structure, high electrical and thermal conductivity and low noise also make GNRs a possible alternative to copper for integrated circuit interconnects.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-nanoribbon] Research is exploring the creation of quantum dots by changing the width of GNRs at select points along the ribbon, creating quantum confinement.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-nanoribbon] Heterojunctions inside single graphene nanoribbons have been realized, among which structures that have been shown to function as tunnel barriers.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-nanoribbon] The electronic properties in external field such as static electric or magnetic field have been extensively studied.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-nanoribbon] The various levels of the tight-binding model as well as first principles calculations have been employed for such studies.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-nanoribbon] For zigzag nanoribbons the most interesting effect under an external electric field is inducing of half-metallicity.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-nanoribbon] In a simple tight-binding model the effect of the external in-plane field applied across the ribbon width is the band gap opening between the edge states.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-nanoribbon] However, the first principles spin-polarized calculations demonstrate that the spin up and down species behave differently.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-nanoribbon] One spin projection closes the band gap whereas another increases.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-nanoribbon] As a result, at some critical value of field, the ribbon turns into a metallic for one spin projection (up or down) and an insulating for another spin (down or up).
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-nanoribbon] In this way, half-metallicity that may be useful for spintronics applications is induced.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-nanoribbon] Armchair ribbons behave differently from their zigzag siblings.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-nanoribbon] They usually feature a band gap that closes under an external in-plane electric field.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-nanoribbon] At some critical value of the field the gap fully closes forming a Dirac cone linear crossing, see Fig.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-nanoribbon] This intriguing result have been corroborated by the density functional theory calculations and explained in a simplified tight-binding model.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-nanoribbon] It does not depend on the chemical composition of the ribbon edges, for example both fluorine and chorine atoms can be used for the ribbon edge passivation instead of a usual hydrogen.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-nanoribbon] Also this effect can be induced by chemical co-doping, i.e. by placing nitrogen and boron atoms atop the ribbon at its opposite sides.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-nanoribbon] Modelwise the effect can be explained by a pair of cis-polyacetylene chains placed at a distance corresponding to the ribbon width and subjected to the different gate potentials.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-nanoribbon] Bearded ribbons with Klen-type edges behave in the tight-binding model approximation similar to zigzag ribbons.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-nanoribbon] Namely, the band gap opens between the edge states.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-nanoribbon] Due to chemical instability of this type of the edge configuration, such ribbons are normally excluded from the publications.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-nanoribbon] Whether they can at least hypothetically exhibit half-metallicity in external in-plane fields similar to zigzag nanoribbons is not yet clear.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-nanoribbon] A vast family of cousins of the above ribbons with both similar edges is the class of ribbons combining non-equivalent edge geometries in a single ribbon.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-nanoribbon] One of the simplest examples can be a half-bearded nanoribbon.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-nanoribbon] Such ribbons, in principle, could be more stable than nanoribbons with two bearded edges because they could be realized via asymmetric hydrogenation of zigzag ribbons.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-nanoribbon] In the nearest neighbor tight-binding model and in non-spin-polarized density functional theory calculations such ribbons exhibit chiral anomaly structure.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-nanoribbon] The fully flat band of a pristine half-bearded nanoribbon subjected to the in-plane external electric field demonstrates unidirectional linear dispersions with group velocities of opposite directions around each of the two Dirac points.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-nanoribbon] At high fields, the linear bands around the Dirac points transform into a wiggly cubic-like dispersions.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-nanoribbon] This nontrivial behavior is favorable for the field-tunable dissipationless transport.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-nanoribbon] The drastic transformation from fully flat to linear and then cubic-like band allows for a continuum ${\vec {k}}\cdot {\vec {p}}$ model description based on the Dirac equation.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-nanoribbon] The Dirac equation supplemented with the suitable boundary conditions breaking the inversion/mirror symmetry and a single field strength parameter admits an analytic solution in terms of Airy-like special functions.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-nanoribbon] Since the two-dimensional graphene sheet with strong bonding is known to be one of the stiffest materials, graphene nanoribbons Young's modulus also has a value of over 1 TPa.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-nanoribbon] The Young's modulus, shear modulus and Poisson's ratio of graphene nanoribbons are different with varying sizes (with different length and width) and shapes.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-nanoribbon] These mechanical properties are anisotropic and would usually be discussed in two in-plane directions, parallel and perpendicular to the one-dimensional periodic direction.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-nanoribbon] Mechanical properties here will be a little bit different from the two-dimensional graphene sheets because of the distinct geometry, bond length, and bond strength particularly at the edge of graphene nanoribbons.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-nanoribbon] It is possible to tune these nanomechanical properties with further chemical doping to change the bonding environment at the edge of graphene nanoribbons.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-nanoribbon] While increasing the width of graphene nanoribbons, the mechanical properties will converge to the value measured on the graphene sheets.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-nanoribbon] One analysis predicted the high Young's modulus for armchair graphene nanoribbons to be around 1.24 TPa by the molecular dynamics method.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-nanoribbon] They also showed the nonlinear elastic behaviors with higher-order terms in the stress-strain curve.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-nanoribbon] In the higher strain region, it would need even higher-order (>3) to fully describe the nonlinear behavior.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-nanoribbon] Other scientists also reported the nonlinear elasticity by the finite element method, and found that Young's modulus, tensile strength, and ductility of armchair graphene nanoribbons are all greater than those of zigzag graphene nanoribbons.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-nanoribbon] Another report predicted the linear elasticity for the strain between -0.02 and 0.02 on the zigzag graphene nanoribbons by the density functional theory model.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-nanoribbon] Within the linear region, the electronic properties would be relatively stable under the slightly changing geometry.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-nanoribbon] The energy gaps increase from -0.02 eV to 0.02 eV for the strain between -0.02 and 0.02, which provides the feasibilities for future engineering applications.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-nanoribbon] The tensile strength of the armchair graphene nanoribbons is 175 GPa with the great ductility of 30.26% fracture strain, which shows the greater mechanical properties comparing to the value of 130 GPa and 25% experimentally measured on monolayer graphene.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-nanoribbon] As expected, graphene nanoribbons with smaller width would completely break down faster, since the ratio of the weaker edged bonds increased.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-nanoribbon] While the tensile strain on graphene nanoribbons reached its maximum, C-C bonds would start to break and then formed much bigger rings to make materials weaker until fracture.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-nanoribbon] The earliest numerical results on the optical properties of graphene nanoribbons were obtained by Lin and Shyu in 2000.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-nanoribbon] The different selection rules for optical transitions in graphene nanoribbons with armchair and zigzag edges were reported.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-nanoribbon] These results were supplemented by a comparative study of zigzag nanoribbons with single wall armchair carbon nanotubes by Hsu and Reichl in 2007.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-nanoribbon] It was demonstrated that selection rules in zigzag ribbons are different from those in carbon nanotube and the eigenstates in zigzag ribbons can be classified as either symmetric or antisymmetric.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-nanoribbon] Also, it was predicted that edge states should play an important role in the optical absorption of zigzag nanoribbons.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-nanoribbon] Optical transitions between the edge and bulk states should enrich the low-energy region ( $<3$ eV) of the absorption spectrum by strong absorption peaks.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-nanoribbon] Analytical derivation of the numerically obtained selection rules was presented in 2011.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-nanoribbon] The selection rule for the incident light polarized parallel (longitudinally) to the zigzag ribbon axis is that $\Delta J=J_{2}-J_{1}$ is odd, where $J_{1}$ and $J_{2}$ enumerate the energy bands, while for the perpendicular polarization $\Delta J$ is even.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-nanoribbon] Intraband (intersubband) transitions between the conduction or valence sub-bands are also allowed in parallel polarization if $\Delta J$ is even.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-nanoribbon] For perpendicular polarization the intraband transitions between the conduction or valence sub-bands are allowed when $\Delta J$ is odd.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-nanoribbon] For graphene nanoribbons with armchair edges the selection rules are $\Delta J$ is odd for the perpendicular and $\Delta J=0$ for the parallel polarization of the incident light.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-nanoribbon] Similar to carbon tubes the intersubband transitions in parallel polarization are forbidden for armchair graphene nanoribbons though they are allowed for the perpendicular polarization and $\Delta J$ being odd.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-nanoribbon] Despite different selection rules in single wall armchair carbon nanotubes and zigzag graphene nanoribbons a hidden correlation of the absorption peaks originating from the bulk states is predicted.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-nanoribbon] The correlation of the absorption peaks in armchair tubes and zigzag ribbons takes place when the matching condition $N_{t}=2N_{r}+4$ holds even though the energy bands of such a tube and ribbon do not align precisely.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-nanoribbon] A similar correlation between bulk absorption peaks can be obtained for armchair nanotubes and nanoribbons with bearded edges, but in this case the matching conditions alters to $N_{t}=2N_{r}+2$ .
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-nanoribbon] These results obtained within the nearest-neighbor approximation of the tight-binding model have been corroborated with first principles density functional theory calculations for zigzag nanoribbons and armchair tubes taking into account exchange and correlation effects.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-nanoribbon] First-principle calculations with quasiparticle corrections and many-body effects explored the electronic and optical properties of graphene-based materials.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-nanoribbon] With GW calculation, the properties of graphene-based materials are accurately investigated, including graphene nanoribbons, edge and surface functionalized armchair graphene nanoribbons and scaling properties in armchair graphene nanoribbons.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-nanoribbon] Graphene nanoribbons can be analyzed by scanning tunneling microscope, Raman spectroscopy, infrared spectroscopy, and X-ray photoelectron spectroscopy.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-nanoribbon] However, analyses of graphene nanoribbon on substrates are difficult using infrared spectroscopy even with a Reflection Absorption Spectrometry method.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-nanoribbon] Thus, a large quantity of graphene nanoribbon is necessary for infrared spectroscopy analyses.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-nanoribbon] Zigzag edges are known to be more reactive than armchair edges, as observed in the dehydrogenation reactivities between the compound with zigzag edges (tetracene) and armchair edges (chrysene).
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-nanoribbon] Also, zigzag edges tends to be more oxidized than armchair edges without gasification.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-nanoribbon] The zigzag edges with longer length can be more reactive as it can be seen from the dependence of the length of acenes on the reactivity.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-nanoribbon] Graphene nanoribbons and their oxidized counterparts called graphene oxide nanoribbons have been investigated as nano-fillers to improve the mechanical properties of polymeric nanocomposites.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-nanoribbon] Increases in the mechanical properties of epoxy composites on loading of graphene nanoribbons were observed.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-nanoribbon] An increase in the mechanical properties of biodegradable polymeric nanocomposites of poly(propylene fumarate) at low weight percentage was achieved by loading of oxidized graphene nanoribbons, fabricated for bone tissue engineering applications.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-nanoribbon] Hybrid imaging modalities, such as photoacoustic (PA) tomography (PAT) and thermoacoustic (TA) tomography (TAT) have been developed for bioimaging applications.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-nanoribbon] PAT/TAT combines advantages of pure ultrasound and pure optical imaging/radio frequency (RF), providing good spatial resolution, great penetration depth and high soft-tissue contrast.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-nanoribbon] GNR synthesized by unzipping single- and multi-walled carbon nanotubes have been reported as contrast agents for photoacoustic and thermoacoustic imaging and tomography.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-nanoribbon] In catalysis, GNRs offer several advantageous features that make them attractive as catalysts or catalyst supports.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-nanoribbon] Firstly, their high surface-to-volume ratio provides abundant active sites for catalytic reactions.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-nanoribbon] This enhanced surface area enables efficient interaction with reactant molecules, leading to improved catalytic performance.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-nanoribbon] Secondly, the edge structure of GNRs plays a crucial role in catalysis.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-nanoribbon] The zigzag and armchair edges of GNRs possess distinctive electronic properties, making them suitable for specific reactions.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-nanoribbon] For instance, the presence of unsaturated carbon atoms at the edges can serve as active sites for adsorption and reaction of various molecules.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-nanoribbon] Moreover, GNRs can be functionalized or doped with heteroatoms to tailor their catalytic properties further.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-nanoribbon] Functionalization with specific groups or doping with elements like silicon, nitrogen, boron, or transition metals can introduce additional active sites or modify the electronic structure, allowing for selective catalytic transformations.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-oxide] The bulk material spontaneously disperses in basic solutions or can be dispersed by sonication in polar solvents to yield monomolecular sheets, known as **graphene oxide** by analogy to graphene, the single-layer form of graphite.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-oxide] Graphene oxide sheets have been used to prepare strong paper-like materials, membranes, thin films, and composite materials.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-oxide] Initially, graphene oxide attracted substantial interest as a possible intermediate for the manufacture of graphene.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-oxide] The graphene obtained by reduction of graphene oxide still has many chemical and structural defects which is a problem for some applications but an advantage for some others.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-oxide] Graphite oxide was first prepared by Oxford chemist Benjamin C.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-oxide] Brodie in 1859 by treating graphite with a mixture of potassium chlorate (KClO3) and fuming nitric acid (HNO3).
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-oxide] He reported synthesis of "paper-like foils" with 0.05 mm thickness.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-oxide] In 1957, Hummers and Offeman developed a safer, quicker, and more efficient process called Hummers' method, using a mixture of sulfuric acid (H2SO4), sodium nitrate (NaNO3), and potassium permanganate (KMnO4), which is still widely used, often with some modifications.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-oxide] Largest monolayer GO with highly intact carbon framework and minimal residual impurity concentrations can be synthesized in inert containers using highly pure reactants and solvents.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-oxide] Graphite oxides exhibit considerable variation in properties with oxidation degree and synthesis method.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-oxide] For example, the temperature point of explosive exfoliation is generally higher for graphite oxide prepared by the Brodie method compared to Hummers graphite oxide, the difference is up to 100 degrees with the same heating rates.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-oxide] The hydration and solvation properties of Brodie and Hummers graphite oxides are also remarkably different.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-oxide] Recently a mixture of H2SO4 and KMnO4 has been used to cut open carbon nanotubes lengthwise, resulting in microscopic flat ribbons of graphene, a few atoms wide, with the edges "capped" by oxygen atoms (=O) or hydroxyl groups (–OH).
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-oxide] Another important advantage of the Tang-Lau method is the control of thickness, ranging from monolayer to multilayers, by adjusting growth parameters.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-oxide] The structure and properties of graphite oxide depend on the particular synthesis method and degree of oxidation.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-oxide] It typically preserves the layer structure of the parent graphite, but the layers are buckled and the interlayer spacing is about two times larger (~0.7 nm) than that of graphite.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-oxide] Strictly speaking "oxide" is an incorrect but historically established name.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-oxide] Besides epoxide groups (bridging oxygen atoms), other functional groups found experimentally are: carbonyl (C=O), hydroxyl (-OH), phenol and for graphite oxides prepared using sulphuric acid (e.g.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-oxide] Hummers method) some impurity of sulphur is often found, for example in a form of organosulfate groups.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-oxide] The detailed structure is still not understood due to the strong disorder and irregular packing of the layers.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-oxide] Graphene oxide layers are about 1.1 ± 0.2 nm thick.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-oxide] Scanning tunneling microscopy shows the presence of local regions where oxygen atoms are arranged in a rectangular pattern with lattice constant 0.27 nm × 0.41 nm.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-oxide] The edges of each layer are terminated with carboxyl and carbonyl groups.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-oxide] X-ray photoelectron spectroscopy shows the presence of several C1*s* peaks, their number and relative intensity depending on the particular oxidation method used.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-oxide] Assignment of these peaks to certain carbon functionalization types is somewhat uncertain and still under debate.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-oxide] For example, one interpretation goes as follows: non-oxygenated ring contexts (284.8 eV), C-O (286.2 eV), C=O (287.8 eV) and O-C=O (289.0 eV).
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-oxide] Graphite oxide is hydrophilic and easily hydrated when exposed to water vapor or immersed in liquid water, resulting in a distinct increase of the inter-planar distance (up to 1.2 nm in saturated state).
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-oxide] Additional water is also incorporated into the interlayer space due to high pressure induced effects.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-oxide] The maximal hydration state of graphite oxide in liquid water corresponds to insertion of 2-3 water monolayers.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-oxide] Cooling the graphite oxide/H2O samples results in "pseudo-negative thermal expansion" and cooling below the freezing point of water results in de-insertion of one water monolayer and lattice contraction.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-oxide] Complete removal of water from the structure seems difficult since heating at 60–80 °C results in partial decomposition and degradation of the material.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-oxide] Similar to water, graphite oxide easily incorporates other polar solvents, e.g. alcohols.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-oxide] However, intercalation of polar solvents occurs significantly different in Brodie and Hummers graphite oxides.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-oxide] Brodie graphite oxide is intercalated at ambient conditions by one monolayer of alcohols and several other solvents (e.g. dimethylformamide and acetone) when liquid solvent is available in excess.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-oxide] Separation of graphite oxide layers is proportional to the size of alcohol molecule.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-oxide] Cooling of Brodie graphite oxide immersed in excess of liquid methanol, ethanol, acetone and dimethylformamide results in step-like insertion of an additional solvent monolayer and lattice expansion.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-oxide] The phase transition detected by X-ray diffraction and differential scanning calorimetry (DSC) is reversible; de-insertion of solvent monolayer is observed when sample is heated back from low temperatures.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-oxide] An additional methanol and ethanol monolayer is reversibly inserted into the structure of Brodie graphite oxide under high pressure conditions.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-oxide] Hummers graphite oxide is intercalated with two methanol or ethanol monolayers at ambient temperature.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-oxide] The interlayer distance of Hummers graphite oxide in an excess of liquid alcohols increases gradually upon temperature decrease, reaching 19.4 and 20.6 Å at 140 K for methanol and ethanol, respectively.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-oxide] The gradual expansion of the Hummers graphite oxide lattice upon cooling corresponds to insertion of at least two additional solvent monolayers.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-oxide] Graphite oxide exfoliates and decomposes when rapidly heated at moderately high temperatures (~280–300 °C) with formation of finely dispersed amorphous carbon, somewhat similar to activated carbon.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-oxide] XRD, FTIR, Raman, XPS, AFM, TEM, SEM/EDX, Thermogravimetric analysis etc. are some common techniques used to characterize GO samples.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-oxide] Experimental results of graphite/graphene oxide have been analyzed by calculation in detail.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-oxide] Since the distribution of oxygen functionalities on GO sheets is polydisperse, fractionation methods can be used to characterize and separate GO sheets on the basis of oxidation.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-oxide] Different synthesis methods give rise to different types of graphene oxide.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-oxide] Even different batches from similar oxidation methods can have differences in their properties due to variations in purification or quenching processes.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-oxide] It is also possible to modify the surface of graphene oxide to change its properties.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-oxide] Graphene oxide has unique surface properties which make it a very good surfactant material stabilizing various emulsion systems.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-oxide] Graphene oxide remains at the interface of the emulsions systems due to the difference in surface energy of the two phases separated by the interface.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-oxide] Graphite oxides absorb moisture in proportion to humidity and swell in liquid water.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-oxide] The amount of water absorbed by graphite oxides depends on the particular synthesis method and shows a strong temperature dependence.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-oxide] Brodie graphite oxide selectively absorbs methanol from water/methanol mixtures in a certain range of methanol concentrations.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-oxide] Membranes prepared from graphite oxides (recently more often called "graphene oxide" membranes) are vacuum tight and impermeable to nitrogen and oxygen, but are permeable to water vapors.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-oxide] The membranes are also impermeable to "substances of lower molecular weight".
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-oxide] Permeation of graphite and graphene oxide membranes by polar solvents is possible due to swelling of the graphite oxide structure.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-oxide] The membranes in swelled state are also permeable by gases, e.g. helium.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-oxide] Graphene oxide sheets are chemically reactive in liquid water, leading them to acquire a small negative charge.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-oxide] The interlayer distance of dried graphite oxides was reported as ~6–7 Å but in liquid water it increases up to 11–13 Å at room temperature.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-oxide] The lattice expansion becomes stronger at lower temperatures.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-oxide] The inter-layer distance in diluted NaOH reached infinity, resulting in dispersion of graphite oxide into single-layered graphene oxide sheets in solution.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-oxide] Graphite oxide can be used as a cation exchange membrane for materials such as KCl, HCl, CaCl2, MgCl2, BaCl2 solutions.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-oxide] The membranes were permeable by large alkali ions as they are able to penetrate between graphene oxide layers.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-oxide] Nonlinear optical materials are of great importance for ultrafast photonics and optoelectronics.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-oxide] Recently, the giant optical nonlinearities of graphene oxide (GO) has proven useful for a number of applications.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-oxide] For example, the optical limiting of GO is indispensable in the protection of sensitive instruments from laser-induced damage.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-oxide] And the saturable absorption can be used for pulse compression, mode-locking and Q-switching.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-oxide] Also, the nonlinear refraction (Kerr effect) is crucial for applications including all-optical switching, signal regeneration, and fast optical communications.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-oxide] One of the most intriguing and unique properties of GO is that its electrical and optical properties can be tuned dynamically by manipulating the content of oxygen-containing groups through either chemical or physical reduction methods.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-oxide] And metal nanoparticles can greatly enhance the optical nonlinearity and fluorescence of graphene oxide.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-oxide] Graphite oxide has attracted much interest as a possible route for the large-scale production and manipulation of graphene, a material with extraordinary electronic properties.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-oxide] Graphite oxide itself is an insulator, almost a semiconductor, with differential conductivity between 1 and 5×10−3 S/cm at a bias voltage of 10 V.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-oxide] However, being hydrophilic, graphite oxide disperses readily in water, breaking up into macroscopic flakes, mostly one layer thick.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-oxide] Chemical reduction of these flakes would yield a suspension of graphene flakes.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-oxide] It was argued that the first experimental observation of graphene was reported by Hanns-Peter Boehm in 1962.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-oxide] In this early work the existence of monolayer reduced graphene oxide flakes was demonstrated.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-oxide] The contribution of Boehm was recently acknowledged by Andre Geim, the Nobel Prize winner for graphene research.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-oxide] Partial reduction can be achieved by treating the suspended graphene oxide with hydrazine hydrate at 100 °C for 24 hours, by exposing graphene oxide to hydrogen plasma for a few seconds, or by exposure to a strong pulse of light, such as that of a xenon flash.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-oxide] Due to the oxidation protocol, manifold defects already present in graphene oxide hamper the effectiveness of the reduction.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-oxide] Thus, the graphene quality obtained after reduction is limited by the precursor quality (graphene oxide) and the efficiency of the reducing agent.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-oxide] However, the conductivity of the graphene obtained by this route is below 10 S/cm, and the charge mobility is between 0.1 and 10 cm2/Vs.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-oxide] These values are much greater than the oxide's, but still a few orders of magnitude lower than those of pristine graphene.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-oxide] Recently, the synthetic protocol for graphite oxide was optimized and almost intact graphene oxide with a preserved carbon framework was obtained.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-oxide] Reduction of this almost intact graphene oxide performs much better and the mobility values of charge carriers exceeds 1000 cm2/Vs for the best quality of flakes.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-oxide] Inspection with the atomic force microscope shows that the oxygen bonds distort the carbon layer, creating a pronounced intrinsic roughness in the oxide layers which persists after reduction.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-oxide] These defects also show up in Raman spectra of graphene oxide.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-oxide] Large amounts of graphene sheets may also be produced through thermal methods.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-oxide] For example, in 2006 a method was discovered that simultaneously exfoliates and reduces graphite oxide by rapid heating (>2000 °C/min) to 1050 °C.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-oxide] At this temperature, carbon dioxide is released as the oxygen functionalities are removed and it explosively separates the sheets as it comes out.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-oxide] The temperature of reduction is important for the oxygen content of the final product, with higher degree of reduction for higher reduction temperatures.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-oxide] Exposing a film of graphite oxide to the laser of a LightScribe DVD has also revealed to produce quality graphene at a low cost.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-oxide] Graphene oxide has also been reduced to graphene *in situ*, using a 3D printed pattern of engineered *E. coli* bacteria.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-oxide] Coupling of graphene oxide with biomolecules such as peptide, proteins and enzymes enhances its biomedical applications.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-oxide] Currently, researchers are focused on reducing graphene oxide using non-toxic substances; tea and coffee powder, lemon extract and various plants based antioxidants are widely used.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-oxide] Graphite oxides were studied for desalination of water using reverse osmosis beginning in the 1960s.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-oxide] In 2011, additional results from research were published.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-oxide] In 2013, Lockheed Martin announced their Perforene graphene filter.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-oxide] Lockheed claims the filter reduces energy costs for reverse osmosis desalination by 99%.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-oxide] Lockheed claimed that the filter was 500 times thinner than the best filter on the market, 1,000 times stronger, and required 1% of the pressure.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-oxide] The product was not expected to be released until 2020.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-oxide] Another study showed that graphite oxide could be engineered to allow water to pass while retaining some larger ions.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-oxide] Narrow capillaries allow rapid permeation by mono- or bilayer water.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-oxide] Multilayer laminates have a structure similar to nacre, which provides mechanical strength in water-free conditions.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-oxide] Helium cannot pass through the membranes in humidity-free conditions, but penetrates easily when exposed to humidity, whereas water vapor passes with no resistance.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-oxide] Dry laminates are vacuum-tight, but immersed in water, they act as molecular sieves, blocking some solutes.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-oxide] A third project produced graphene sheets with subnanoscale (0.40 ± 0.24 nm) pores.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-oxide] The graphene was bombarded with gallium ions, which disrupt carbon bonds.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-oxide] Etching the result with an oxidizing solution produces a hole at each spot struck by a gallium ion.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-oxide] The length of time spent in the oxidizing solution determined the average pore size.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-oxide] Pore density reached 5 trillion pores per square centimeter, while retaining structural integrity.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-oxide] The pores permitted cationss transport after short oxidation periods, consistent with electrostatic repulsion from negatively charged functional groups at pore edges.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-oxide] After longer oxidation periods, sheets were permeable to salt but not larger organic molecules.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-oxide] In 2015, a team fabricated a graphene oxide home water purification system resembling a "tea bag" that, over the course of a day, can remove 95% of heavy metals when immersed in a drinking-water pot.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-oxide] A composite comprising small NiFe2O4 ferrimagnetic nanoparticles and partially reduced graphene oxide functionalized with nitrogen atoms was successfully used to remove Cr(III) ions from water.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-oxide] The advantage of this nanocomposite is that it can be magnetically separated from water.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-oxide] One project layered carbon atoms in a honeycomb structure, forming a hexagon-shaped crystal that measured about 0.1 millimeters in width and length, with subnanometer holes.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-oxide] Later work increased the membrane size to on the order of several millimeters.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-oxide] Graphene attached to a polycarbonate support structure was initially effective at removing salt.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-oxide] However, defects formed in the graphene.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-oxide] Filling larger defects with nylon and small defects with hafnium metal, followed by a layer of oxide, restored the filtration effect.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-oxide] In 2016, engineers developed graphene-based films powered by the sun that can filter dirty/salty water.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-oxide] Bacteria were used to produce a material consisting of two nanocellulose layers.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-oxide] The lower layer contains pristine cellulose, while the top layer contains cellulose and graphene oxide, which absorb sunlight and produce heat.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-oxide] The system draws water from below into the material.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-oxide] The water diffuses into the higher layer, where it evaporates, leaving behind any contaminants.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-oxide] The vapor condenses on top, where it can be captured.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-oxide] The film is produced by repeatedly adding a fluid coating that hardens.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-oxide] Bacteria produce nanocellulose fibers with interspersed graphene oxide flakes.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-oxide] The film is light and easily manufactured at scale.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-oxide] Optically transparent, multilayer films made from *graphene oxide*are impermeable under dry conditions.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-oxide] Exposed to water (or water vapor), they allow passage of molecules below a certain size.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-oxide] The films consist of millions of randomly stacked flakes, leaving nano-sized capillaries between them.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-oxide] Closing these nanocapillaries using chemical reduction with hydroiodic acid creates "reduced graphene oxide" (r-GO) films that are completely impermeable to gases, liquids or strong chemicals greater than 100 nanometers thick.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-oxide] Glassware or copper plates covered with such a graphene "paint" can be used as containers for corrosive acids.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-oxide] Graphene-coated plastic films could be used in medical packaging to improve shelf life.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-oxide] Layer-by-layer coatings based on amine-modified graphene oxide and Nafion show excellent antimicrobial performance that is not compromised when heated for 2 hours at 200 °C.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-oxide] Dispersed graphene oxide flakes can also be sifted out of the dispersion (as in paper manufacture) and pressed to make an exceedingly strong graphene oxide paper.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-oxide] Graphene oxide has been used in DNA analysis applications.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-oxide] The large planar surface of graphene oxide allows simultaneous quenching of multiple DNA probes labeled with different dyes, providing the detection of multiple DNA targets in the same solution.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-oxide] Further advances in graphene oxide based DNA sensors could result in very inexpensive rapid DNA analysis.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-oxide] Recently a group of researchers, from university of L'Aquila (Italy), discovered new wetting properties of graphene oxide thermally reduced in ultra-high vacuum up to 900 °C.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-oxide] They found a correlation between the surface chemical composition, the surface free energy and its polar and dispersive components, giving a rationale for the wetting properties of graphene oxide and reduced graphene oxide.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-oxide] Graphene oxide has been demonstrated as a flexible free-standing battery anode material for room temperature lithium-ion and sodium-ion batteries.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-oxide] It is also being studied as a high surface area conducting agent in lithium-sulfur battery cathodes.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-oxide] The functional groups on graphene oxide can serve as sites for chemical modification and immobilization of active species.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-oxide] This approach allows for the creation of hybrid architectures for electrode materials.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-oxide] Recent examples of this have been implemented in lithium-ion batteries, which are known for being rechargeable at the cost of low capacity limits.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-oxide] Graphene oxide-based composites functionalized with metal oxides and sulfides have been shown in recent research to induce enhanced battery performance.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-oxide] This has similarly been adapted into applications in supercapacitors, since the electronic properties of graphene oxide allow it to bypass some of the more prevalent restrictions of typical transition metal oxide electrodes.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-oxide] Research in this field is developing, with additional exploration into methods involving nitrogen doping and pH adjustment to improve capacitance.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-oxide] Additionally, research into reduced graphene oxide sheets, which display superior electronic properties akin to pure graphene, is currently being explored.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-oxide] Reduced graphene oxide greatly increases the conductivity and efficiency, while sacrificing some flexibility and structural integrity.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-oxide] The optical lens has been playing a critical role in almost all areas of science and technology since its invention about 3000 years ago.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-oxide] With the advances in micro- and nanofabrication techniques, continued miniaturization of the conventional optical lenses has always been requested for various applications such as communications, sensors, data storage and a wide range of other technology-driven and consumer-driven industries.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-oxide] Specifically, ever smaller sizes, as well as thinner thicknesses of micro lenses, are highly needed for subwavelength optics or nano-optics with extremely small structures, particularly for visible and near-IR applications.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-oxide] Also, as the distance scale for optical communications shrinks, the required feature sizes of micro lenses are rapidly pushed down.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-oxide] Recently, the excellent properties of newly discovered graphene oxide provide novel solutions to overcome the challenges of current planar focusing devices.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-oxide] As a result, the overall lens thickness can be potentially reduced by more than ten times.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-oxide] Also, the linear optical absorption of GO is found to increase as the reduction of GO deepens, which results in transmission contrast between GO and rGO and therefore provides an amplitude modulation mechanism.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-oxide] Moreover, both the refractive index and the optical absorption are found to be dispersionless over a broad wavelength range from visible to near infrared.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-oxide] Finally, GO film offers flexible patterning capability by using the maskless DLW method, which reduces the manufacturing complexity and requirements.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-oxide] As a result, a novel ultrathin planar lens on a GO thin film has been realized recently using the DLW method.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-oxide] The distinct advantage of the GO flat lens is that phase modulation and amplitude modulation can be achieved simultaneously, which are attributed to the giant refractive index modulation and the variable linear optical absorption of GO during its reduction process, respectively.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-oxide] Due to the enhanced wavefront shaping capability, the lens thickness is pushed down to subwavelength scale (~200 nm), which is thinner than all current dielectric lenses (~ μm scale).
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-oxide] The focusing intensities and the focal length can be controlled effectively by varying the laser powers and the lens sizes, respectively.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-oxide] Thereafter, the focal length can be reduced to as small as 0.8 μm, which would potentially increase the numerical aperture (NA) and the focusing resolution.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-oxide] The full-width at half-maximum (FWHM) of 320 nm at the minimum focal spot using a 650 nm input beam has been demonstrated experimentally, which corresponding to the effective NA of 1.24 (n=1.5), the largest NA of current micro lenses.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-oxide] Furthermore, ultra-broadband focusing capability from 500 nm to as far as 2 μm have been realized with the same planar lens, which is still a major challenge of focusing in infrared range due to limited availability of suitable materials and fabrication technology.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-oxide] Photocatalytic water splitting is an artificial photosynthesis process in which water is dissociated into hydrogen (H2) and oxygen (O2), using artificial or natural light.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-oxide] Methods such as photocatalytic water splitting are currently being investigated to produce hydrogen as a clean source of energy.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-oxide] The superior electron mobility and high surface area of graphene oxide sheets suggest it may be implemented as a catalyst that meets the requirements for this process.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-oxide] Specifically, graphene oxide's compositional functional groups of epoxide (-O-) and hydroxide (-OH) allow for more flexible control in the water splitting process.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-oxide] This flexibility can be used to tailor the band gap and band positions that are targeted in photocatalytic water splitting.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-oxide] Recent research experiments have demonstrated that the photocatalytic activity of graphene oxide containing a band gap within the required limits has produced effective splitting results, particularly when used with 40-50% coverage at a 2:1 hydroxide:epoxide ratio.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-oxide] When used in composite materials with CdS (a typical catalyst used in photocatalytic water splitting), graphene oxide nanocomposites have been shown to exhibit increased hydrogen production and quantum efficiency.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-oxide] Graphene oxide is also being explored for its applications in hydrogen storage.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-oxide] Hydrogen molecules can be stored among the oxygen-based functional groups found throughout the sheet.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-oxide] This hydrogen storage capability can be further manipulated by modulating the interlayer distance between sheets, as well as making changes to the pore sizes.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-oxide] Research in transition metal decoration on carbon sorbents to enhance hydrogen binding energy has led to experiments with titanium and magnesium anchored to hydroxyl groups, allowing for the binding of multiple hydrogen molecules.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-oxide] Graphene oxide has been studied for its promising uses in a wide variety of nanomedical applications including tissue engineering, cancer treatment, medical imaging, and drug delivery.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-oxide] Its physiochemical properties allow for a structure to regulate the behaviour of stem cells, with the potential to assist in the intracellular delivery of DNA, growth factors, and synthetic proteins that could allow for the repair and regeneration of muscle tissue.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-oxide] Due to its unique behaviour in biological environments, GO has also been proposed as a novel material in early cancer diagnosis.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-oxide] It has also been explored for its uses in vaccines and immunotherapy, including as a dual-use adjuvant and carrier of biomedical materials.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-oxide] In September 2020, researchers at the Shanghai National Engineering Research Center for Nanotechnology in China filed a patent for use of graphene oxide in a recombinant vaccine under development against SARS-CoV-2.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-oxide] Several typical mechanisms underlying graphene (oxide) nanomaterial's toxicity have been revealed, for instance, physical destruction, oxidative stress, DNA damage, inflammatory response, apoptosis, autophagy, and necrosis.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-oxide] In these mechanisms, toll-like receptors (TLR), transforming growth factor-beta (TGF-β) and tumor necrosis factor-alpha (TNF-α) dependent-pathways are involved in the signalling pathway network, and oxidative stress plays a crucial role in these pathways.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-oxide] Many experiments have shown that graphene (oxide) nanomaterials have toxic side effects in many biological applications, but more in-depth study of toxicity mechanisms is needed.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-oxide] According to the USA FDA, graphene, graphene oxide, and reduced graphene oxide elicit toxic effects both in vitro and in vivo.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-oxide] Graphene-family nanomaterials (GFN) are not approved by the USA FDA for human consumption.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-p01] In technical terms, graphene is a carbon allotrope consisting of a single layer of atoms arranged in a honeycomb planar nanostructure.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-p01] The name "graphene" is derived from "graphite" and the suffix -ene, indicating the presence of double bonds within the carbon structure.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-p01] Graphene is known for its exceptionally high tensile strength, electrical conductivity, transparency, and being the thinnest two-dimensional material in the world.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-p01] Despite the nearly transparent nature of a single graphene sheet, graphite (formed from stacked layers of graphene) appears black because it absorbs all visible light wavelengths.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-p01] On a microscopic scale, graphene is the strongest material ever measured.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-p01] The existence of graphene was first theorized in 1947 by Philip R.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-p01] Wallace during his research on graphite's electronic properties, while the term *graphene* was first defined by Hanns-Peter Boehm in 1987, when he and coworkers isolated single sheets from graphite.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-p01] In 2004, the material was isolated and characterized by Andre Geim and Konstantin Novoselov at the University of Manchester using a piece of graphite and adhesive tape.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-p01] In 2010, Geim and Novoselov were awarded the Nobel Prize in Physics for their "groundbreaking experiments regarding the two-dimensional material graphene".
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-p01] While small amounts of graphene are easy to produce using the method by which it was originally isolated, attempts to scale and automate the manufacturing process for mass production have had limited success out of concern for cost-effectiveness and quality control.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-p01] The global graphene market was $9 million in 2012, with most of the demand from research and development in semiconductors, electronics, electric batteries, and composites.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-p01] The IUPAC (International Union of Pure and Applied Chemistry) advises using the term "graphite" for the three-dimensional material and reserving "graphene" for discussions about the properties or reactions of single-atom layers.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-p01] A narrower definition, of "isolated or free-standing graphene", requires that the layer be sufficiently isolated from its environment, but would include layers suspended or transferred to silicon dioxide or silicon carbide.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-p01] In 1859, Benjamin Brodie noted the highly lamellar structure of thermally reduced graphite oxide.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-p01] Researchers used X-ray crystallography in an attempt to determine the structure of graphite.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-p01] The lack of large single crystal graphite specimens contributed to the independent development of X-ray powder diffraction by Peter Debye and Paul Scherrer in 1915, and Albert Hull in 1916.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-p01] However, neither of their proposed structures was correct.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-p01] Haenni described the properties of graphite oxide paper.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-p01] The structure of graphite was successfully determined from single-crystal X-ray diffraction by J.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-p01] Bernal in 1924, while subsequent research tweaked the unit cell parameters.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-p01] The theory of graphene was first explored by P.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-p01] Wallace in 1947 as a starting point for understanding the electronic properties of 3D graphite.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-p01] The emergent massless Dirac equation was separately pointed out in 1984 by Gordon Walter Semenoff, and by David P.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-p01] Semenoff emphasized the occurrence in a magnetic field of an electronic Landau level precisely at the Dirac point.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-p01] This level is responsible for the anomalous integer Quantum Hall effect.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-p01] Transmission electron microscopy (TEM) images of thin graphite samples consisting of a few graphene layers were published by G.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-p01] Eventually, single layers were also observed directly.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-p01] Single layers of graphite were also observed by transmission electron microscopy within bulk materials, particularly inside soot obtained by chemical exfoliation.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-p01] From 1961 to 1962, Hanns-Peter Boehm published a study of extremely thin flakes of graphite.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-p01] The study measured flakes as small as ~0.4 nm, which is around 3 atomic layers of amorphous carbon.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-p01] This was the best possible resolution for TEMs in the 1960s.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-p01] However, it is impossible to distinguish between suspended monolayer and multilayer graphene by their TEM contrasts, and the only known method is to analyze the relative intensities of various diffraction spots.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-p01] The first reliable TEM observations of monolayers are likely given in references 24 and 26 of Geim and Novoselov's 2007 review.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-p01] In 1975, van Bommel et al. epitaxially grew a single layer of graphite on top of silicon carbide.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-p01] Others grew single layers of carbon atoms on other materials.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-p01] This "epitaxial graphene" consists of a single-atom-thick hexagonal lattice of sp2-bonded carbon atoms, as in free-standing graphene.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-p01] However, there is significant charge transfer between the two materials and, in some cases, hybridization between the d-orbitals of the substrate atoms and π orbitals of graphene, which significantly alter the electronic structure compared to that of free-standing graphene.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-p01] Boehm et al. coined the term "graphene" for the hypothetical single-layer structure in 1986.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-p01] The term was used again in 1987 to describe single sheets of graphite as a constituent of graphite intercalation compounds, which can be seen as crystalline salts of the intercalant and graphene.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-p01] It was also used in the descriptions of carbon nanotubes by R.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-p01] Saito and Mildred and Gene Dresselhaus in 1992, and in the description of polycyclic aromatic hydrocarbons in 2000 by S.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-p01] Efforts to make thin films of graphite by mechanical exfoliation started in 1990.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-p01] Initial attempts employed exfoliation techniques similar to the drawing method.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-p01] Multilayer samples down to 10 nm in thickness were obtained.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-p01] Dudman filed for a patent in the US on a method to produce graphene by repeatedly peeling off layers from a graphite flake adhered to a substrate, achieving a graphite thickness of 0.00001 inches (0.00025 millimetres).
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-p01] The key to success was the ability to quickly and efficiently identify graphene flakes on the substrate using optical microscopy, which provided a small but visible contrast between the graphene and the substrate.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-p01] Another U.S. patent was filed in the same year by Bor Z.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-p01] Huang for a method to produce graphene-based on exfoliation followed by attrition.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-p01] In 2014, inventor Larry Fullerton patented a process for producing single-layer graphene sheets by graphene's strong diamagnetic properties.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-p01] Graphene was properly isolated and characterized in 2004 by Andre Geim and Konstantin Novoselov at the University of Manchester.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-p01] They pulled graphene layers from graphite with a common adhesive tape in a process called micro-mechanical cleavage, colloquially referred to as the Scotch tape technique.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-p01] The graphene flakes were then transferred onto a thin silicon dioxide layer on a silicon plate ("wafer").
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-p01] The silica electrically isolated the graphene and weakly interacted with it, providing nearly charge-neutral graphene layers.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-p01] The silicon beneath the SiO 2 could be used as a "back gate" electrode to vary the charge density in the graphene over a wide range.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-p01] This work resulted in the two winning the Nobel Prize in Physics in 2010 for their groundbreaking experiments with graphene.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-p01] Their publication and the surprisingly easy preparation method that they described, sparked a "graphene gold rush".
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-p01] Research expanded and split off into many different subfields, exploring different exceptional properties of the material—quantum mechanical, electrical, chemical, mechanical, optical, magnetic, etc.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-p01] Since the early 2000s, several companies and research laboratories have been working to develop commercial applications of graphene.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-p01] In 2014, a National Graphene Institute was established with that purpose at the University of Manchester, with a £60 million initial funding.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-p01] In North East England two commercial manufacturers, Applied Graphene Materials and Thomas Swan Limited have begun manufacturing.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-p01] Cambridge Nanosystems is a large-scale graphene powder production facility in East Anglia.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-p01] Graphene is a single layer of carbon atoms tightly bound in a hexagonal honeycomb lattice.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-p01] It is an allotrope of carbon in the form of a plane of sp2-bonded atoms with a molecular bond length R = 0.142 nm (1.42 Å).
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-p01] The (two-dimensional) density of graphene is therefore $0.0399/0.0542=0.762$ mg per square meter.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-p01] In a graphene sheet, each atom is connected to its three nearest carbon neighbors by σ-bonds, and a delocalized π-bond, which contributes to a valence band that extends over the whole sheet.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-p01] This type of bonding is also seen in polycyclic aromatic hydrocarbons.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-p01] The valence band is touched by a conduction band, making graphene a semimetal with unusual electronic properties that are best described by theories for massless relativistic particles.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-p01] Charge carriers in graphene show linear, rather than quadratic, dependence of energy on momentum, and field-effect transistors with graphene can be made that show bipolar conduction.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-p01] Charge transport is ballistic over long distances; the material exhibits large quantum oscillations and large nonlinear diamagnetism.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-p01] Three of the four outer-shell electrons of each atom in a graphene sheet occupy three sp2 hybrid orbitals – a combination of orbitals s, px and py — that are shared with the three nearest atoms, forming σ-bonds.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-p01] The length of these bonds is about 0.142 nanometers.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-p01] The remaining outer-shell electron occupies a pz orbital that is oriented perpendicularly to the plane.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-p01] These orbitals hybridize together to form two half-filled bands of free-moving electrons, π, and π∗, which are responsible for most of graphene's notable electronic properties.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-p01] Recent quantitative estimates of aromatic stabilization and limiting size derived from the enthalpies of hydrogenation (ΔHhydro) agree well with the literature reports.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-p01] Graphene sheets stack to form graphite with an interplanar spacing of 0.335 nm (3.35 Å).
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-p01] Graphene sheets in solid form usually show evidence in diffraction for graphite's (002) layering.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-p01] This is true of some single-walled nanostructures.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-p01] However, unlayered graphene displaying only (hk0) rings have been observed in the core of presolar graphite onions.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-p01] TEM studies show faceting at defects in flat graphene sheets and suggest a role for two-dimensional crystallization from a melt.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-p01] The hexagonal lattice structure of isolated, single-layer graphene can be directly seen with transmission electron microscopy (TEM) of sheets of graphene suspended between bars of a metallic grid.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-p01] Some of these images showed a "rippling" of the flat sheet, with an amplitude of about one nanometer.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-p01] These ripples may be intrinsic to the material as a result of the instability of two-dimensional crystals, or may originate from the ubiquitous dirt seen in all TEM images of graphene.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-p01] Photoresist residue, which must be removed to obtain atomic-resolution images, may be the "adsorbates" observed in TEM images, and may explain the observed rippling.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-p01] The hexagonal structure is also seen in scanning tunneling microscope (STM) images of graphene supported on silicon dioxide substrates The rippling seen in these images is caused by the conformation of graphene to the substrates' lattice and is not intrinsic.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-p01] Ab initio calculations show that a graphene sheet is thermodynamically unstable if its size is less than about 20 nm and becomes the most stable fullerene (as within graphite) only for molecules larger than 24,000 atoms.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-p01] Graphene is a zero-gap semiconductor because its conduction and valence bands meet at the Dirac points.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-p01] The Dirac points are six locations in momentum space on the edge of the Brillouin zone, divided into two non-equivalent sets of three points.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-p01] These sets give graphene a valley degeneracy of $g_{v}=2$ .
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-p01] In contrast, for traditional semiconductors, the primary point of interest is generally Γ, where momentum is zero.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-p01] If the in-plane direction is confined rather than infinite, its electronic structure changes.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-p01] These confined structures are referred to as graphene nanoribbons.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-p01] If the nanoribbon has a "zig-zag" edge, the bandgap remains zero.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-p01] If it has an "armchair" edge, the bandgap is non-zero.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-p01] Graphene's honeycomb structure can be viewed as two interleaving triangular lattices.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-p01] This perspective has been used to calculate the band structure for a single graphite layer using a tight-binding approximation.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-p01] Electrons propagating through the graphene honeycomb lattice effectively lose their mass, producing quasi-particles described by a 2D analogue of the Dirac equation rather than the Schrödinger equation for spin-⁠1/2⁠ particles.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-p01] The cleavage technique led directly to the first observation of the anomalous quantum Hall effect in graphene in 2005 by Geim's group and by Philip Kim and Yuanbo Zhang.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-p01] This effect provided direct evidence of graphene's theoretically predicted Berry's phase of massless Dirac fermions and proof of the Dirac fermion nature of electrons.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-p01] These effects were previously observed in bulk graphite by Yakov Kopelevich, Igor A.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-p01] When atoms are placed onto the graphene hexagonal lattice, the overlap between the *p*z(π) orbitals and the *s* or the *p*x and *p*y orbitals is zero by symmetry.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-p01] Therefore, *p*z electrons forming the π bands in graphene can be treated independently.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-p01] with the nearest-neighbor (π orbitals) hopping energy *γ*0 ≈ 2.8 eV and the lattice constant *a* ≈ 2.46 Å.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-p01] The conduction and valence bands correspond to the different signs.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-p01] With one *p*z electron per atom in this model, the valence band is fully occupied, while the conduction band is vacant.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-p01] The two bands touch at the zone corners (the *K* point in the Brillouin zone), where there is a zero density of states but no band gap.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-p01] Thus, graphene exhibits a semi-metallic (or zero-gap semiconductor) character, although this is not true for a graphene sheet rolled into a carbon nanotube due to its curvature.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-p01] Two of the six Dirac points are independent, while the rest are equivalent by symmetry.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-p01] Near the *K*-points, the energy depends *linearly* on the wave vector, similar to a relativistic particle.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-p01] Since an elementary cell of the lattice has a basis of two atoms, the wave function has an effective 2-spinor structure.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-p01] Consequently, at low energies even neglecting the true spin, electrons can be described by an equation formally equivalent to the massless Dirac equation.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-p01] Hence, the electrons and holes are called Dirac fermions.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-p01] Here *vF* ~ 106 m/s (.003 c) is the Fermi velocity in graphene, which replaces the velocity of light in the Dirac theory; ${\vec {\sigma }}$ is the vector of the Pauli matrices, $\psi (\mathbf {r} )$ is the two-component wave function of the electrons, and *E* is their energy.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-p01] where the wavevector *q* is measured from the Brillouin zone vertex K, $q=\left|\mathbf {k} -\mathrm {K} \right|$ , and the zero of energy is set to coincide with the Dirac point.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-p01] The equation uses a pseudospin matrix formula that describes two sublattices of the honeycomb lattice.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-p01] Electron waves in graphene propagate within a single-atom layer, making them sensitive to the proximity of other materials such as high-κ dielectrics, superconductors, and ferromagnets.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-p01] Graphene exhibits high electron mobility at room temperature, with values reported in excess of 15000 cm2⋅V−1⋅s−1.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-p01] Hole and electron mobilities are nearly identical.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-p01] The mobility is independent of temperature between 10 K and 100 K, showing minimal change even at room temperature (300 K), suggesting that the dominant scattering mechanism is defect scattering.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-p01] Scattering by graphene's acoustic phonons intrinsically limits room temperature mobility in freestanding graphene to 200000 cm2⋅V−1⋅s−1 at a carrier density of 1012 cm−2.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-p01] The corresponding resistivity of graphene sheets is 10−8 Ω⋅m, lower than the resistivity of silver, which is the lowest known at room temperature.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-p01] However, on SiO 2 substrates, electron scattering by optical phonons of the substrate has a more significant effect than scattering by graphene's phonons, limiting mobility to 40000 cm2⋅V−1⋅s−1.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-p01] Charge transport can be affected by the adsorption of contaminants such as water and oxygen molecules, leading to non-repetitive and large hysteresis I-V characteristics.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-p01] Researchers need to conduct electrical measurements in a vacuum.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-p01] Coating the graphene surface with materials such as SiN, PMMA or h-BN has been proposed for protection.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-p01] In January 2015, the first stable graphene device operation in the air over several weeks was reported for graphene whose surface was protected by aluminum oxide.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-p01] In 2015, lithium-coated graphene exhibited superconductivity, a first for graphene.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-p01] Electrical resistance in 40-nanometer-wide nanoribbons of epitaxial graphene changes in discrete steps.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-p01] The ribbons' conductance exceeds predictions by a factor of 10.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-p01] The ribbons can function more like optical waveguides or quantum dots, allowing electrons to flow smoothly along the ribbon edges.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-p01] In copper, resistance increases proportionally with length as electrons encounter impurities.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-p01] Transport is dominated by two modes: one ballistic and temperature-independent, and the other thermally activated.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-p01] Ballistic electrons resemble those in cylindrical carbon nanotubes.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-p01] At room temperature, resistance increases abruptly at a specific length—the ballistic mode at 16 micrometers and the thermally activated mode at 160 nanometers (1% of the former length).
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-p01] Graphene electrons can traverse micrometer distances without scattering, even at room temperature.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-p01] Despite zero carrier density near the Dirac points, graphene exhibits a minimum conductivity on the order of $4e^{2}/h$ .
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-p01] The origin of this minimum conductivity is still unclear.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-p01] However, rippling of the graphene sheet or ionized impurities in the SiO 2 substrate may lead to local puddles of carriers that allow conduction.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-p01] Several theories suggest that the minimum conductivity should be $4e^{2}/{(\pi }h)$ ; however, most measurements are of the order of $4e^{2}/h$ or greater and depend on impurity concentration.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-p01] Near zero carrier density, graphene exhibits positive photoconductivity and negative photoconductivity at high carrier density, governed by the interplay between photoinduced changes of both the Drude weight and the carrier scattering rate.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-p01] Graphene doped with various gaseous species (both acceptors and donors) can be returned to an undoped state by gentle heating in a vacuum.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-p01] Even for dopant concentrations in excess of 1012 cm−2, carrier mobility exhibits no observable change.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-p01] Graphene doped with potassium in ultra-high vacuum at low temperature can reduce mobility 20-fold.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-p01] The mobility reduction is reversible on heating the graphene to remove the potassium.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-p01] Due to graphene's two dimensions, charge fractionalization (where the apparent charge of individual pseudoparticles in low-dimensional systems is less than a single quantum) is thought to occur.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-p01] It may therefore be a suitable material for constructing quantum computers using anyonic circuits.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-p01] The quantum Hall effect is a quantum mechanical version of the Hall effect, which is the production of transverse (perpendicular to the main current) conductivity in the presence of a magnetic field.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-p01] The quantization of the Hall effect $\sigma _{xy}$ at integer multiples (the "Landau level") of the basic quantity *e*2/*h* (where *e* is the elementary electric charge and *h* is the Planck constant).
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-p01] It can usually be observed only in very clean silicon or gallium arsenide solids at temperatures around 3 K and very high magnetic fields.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-p01] Graphene shows the quantum Hall effect: the conductivity quantization is unusual in that the sequence of steps is shifted by 1/2 with respect to the standard sequence and with an additional factor of 4.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-p01] Graphene's Hall conductivity is $\sigma _{xy}=\pm {4\cdot \left(N+1/2\right)e^{2}}/h$ , where *N* is the Landau level and the double valley and double spin degeneracies give the factor of 4.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-p01] These anomalies are present not only at extremely low temperatures but also at room temperature, i.e. at roughly 20 °C (293 K).
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-p01] This behavior is a direct result of graphene's chiral, massless Dirac electrons.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-p01] In a magnetic field, their spectrum has a Landau level with energy precisely at the Dirac point.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-p01] This level is a consequence of the Atiyah–Singer index theorem and is half-filled in neutral graphene, leading to the "+1/2" in the Hall conductivity.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-p01] Bilayer graphene also shows the quantum Hall effect, but with only one of the two anomalies (i.e. $\sigma _{xy}=\pm {4\cdot N\cdot e^{2}}/h$ ).
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-p01] In the second anomaly, the first plateau at *N* = 0 is absent, indicating that bilayer graphene stays metallic at the neutrality point.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-p01] Unlike normal metals, graphene's longitudinal resistance shows maxima rather than minima for integral values of the Landau filling factor in measurements of the Shubnikov–de Haas oscillations, thus the term "*integral* quantum Hall effect".
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-p01] These oscillations show a phase shift of π, known as Berry's phase.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-p01] Berry's phase arises due to chirality or dependence (locking) of the pseudospin quantum number on the momentum of low-energy electrons near the Dirac points.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-p01] The temperature dependence of the oscillations reveals that the carriers have a non-zero cyclotron mass, despite their zero effective mass in the Dirac-fermion formalism.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-p01] Graphene samples prepared on nickel films, and on both the silicon face and carbon face of silicon carbide, show the anomalous effect directly in electrical measurements.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-p01] Graphitic layers on the carbon face of silicon carbide show a clear Dirac spectrum in angle-resolved photoemission experiments, and the effect is observed in cyclotron resonance and tunneling experiments.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-p01] Graphene's unit cell has two identical carbon atoms and two zero-energy states: one where the electron resides on atom A, and the other on atom B.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-p01] However, if the unit cell's two atoms are not identical, the situation changes.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-p01] Research shows that placing hexagonal boron nitride (h-BN) in contact with graphene can alter the potential felt at atoms A and B sufficiently for the electrons to develop a mass and an accompanying band gap of about 30 meV.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-p01] An arrangement that slightly raises the energy of an electron on atom A relative to atom B gives it a positive mass, while an arrangement that raises the energy of atom B produces a negative electron mass.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-p01] The two versions behave alike and are indistinguishable via optical spectroscopy.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-p01] An electron traveling from a positive-mass region to a negative-mass region must cross an intermediate region where its mass once again becomes zero.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-p01] This region is gapless and therefore metallic.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-p01] Metallic modes bounding semiconducting regions of opposite-sign mass is a hallmark of a topological phase and displays much the same physics as topological insulators.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-p01] If the mass in graphene can be controlled, electrons can be confined to massless regions by surrounding them with massive regions, allowing the patterning of quantum dots, wires, and other mesoscopic structures.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-p01] It also produces one-dimensional conductors along the boundary.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-p01] These wires would be protected against backscattering and could carry currents without dissipation.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-p01] While a single electron exhibits zero effective mass in graphene, as the entire set of electrons is moved with an electric field, the Fermi disk shifts, with both the total kinetic energy E and the magnitude of the total momentum P being increased.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-p01] Since E is minimum when $P=0$ , to the first order, $E\sim P^{2}$ must hold.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-p01] The proportional constant must be given by $1/(2M)$ where M is the collective mass (inertia) of graphene electrons.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-p01] Another view of this is to associate the total kinetic energy with the current.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-p01] Because the total momentum is proportional to the current I , $E\sim I^{2}$ must hold.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-p01] The kinetic inductance, representing the collective inertial effect, is intimately linked to graphene plasmonics, and was directly measured via microwave network analysis in 2014.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-p01] In magnetic fields above 10 tesla, additional plateaus of the Hall conductivity at *σ**xy* = *νe*2/*h* with *ν* = 0, ±1, ±4 are observed.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-p01] A plateau at *ν* = 3 and the fractional quantum Hall effect at *ν* = ⁠1/3⁠ were also reported.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-p01] These observations with *ν* = 0, ±1, ±3, ±4 indicate that the four-fold degeneracy (two valley and two spin degrees of freedom) of the Landau energy levels is partially or completely lifted.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-p01] The Casimir effect is an interaction between disjoint neutral bodies provoked by the fluctuations of the electromagnetic vacuum.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-p01] Mathematically, it can be explained by considering the normal modes of electromagnetic fields, which explicitly depend on the boundary conditions on the interacting bodies' surfaces.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-p01] Due to graphene's strong interaction with the electromagnetic field as a one-atom-thick material, the Casimir effect has garnered significant interest.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-p01] The Van der Waals force (or dispersion force) is also unusual, obeying an inverse cubic asymptotic power law in contrast to the usual inverse quartic law.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-p01] Graphene's permittivity varies with frequency.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-p01] Over a range from microwave to millimeter wave frequencies, it is approximately 3.3.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-p01] This permittivity, combined with its ability to function as both a conductor and as an insulator, theoretically allows compact capacitors made of graphene to store large amounts of electrical energy.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-p01] Graphene exhibits unique optical properties, showing unexpectedly high opacity for an atomic monolayer in vacuum, absorbing approximately *πα* ≈ 2.3% of light from visible to infrared wavelengths, where *α* is the fine-structure constant.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-p01] This is due to the unusual low-energy electronic structure of monolayer graphene, characterized by electron and hole conical bands meeting at the Dirac point, which is qualitatively different from more common quadratic massive bands.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-p01] Based on the Slonczewski–Weiss–McClure (SWMcC) band model of graphite, calculations using Fresnel equations in the thin-film limit account for interatomic distance, hopping values, and frequency, thus assessing optical conductance.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-p01] Experimental verification, though confirmed, lacks the precision required to improve upon existing techniques for determining the fine-structure constant.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-p01] Multi-parametric surface plasmon resonance has been utilized to characterize both the thickness and refractive index of chemical-vapor-deposition (CVD)-grown graphene films.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-p01] At a wavelength of 670 nm (6.7×10−7 m), measured refractive index and extinction coefficient values are 3.135 and 0.897, respectively.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-p01] Thickness determination yielded 3.7 Å across a 0.5mm area, consistent with the 3.35 Å reported for layer-to-layer carbon atom distance of graphite crystals.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-p01] This method is applicable for real-time label-free interactions of graphene with organic and inorganic substances.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-p01] The existence of unidirectional surface plasmons in nonreciprocal graphene-based gyrotropic interfaces has been theoretically demonstrated, offering tunability from THz to near-infrared and visible frequencies by controlling graphene's chemical potential.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-p01] Particularly, the unidirectional frequency bandwidth can be 1– 2 orders of magnitude larger than that achievable with metal under similar magnetic field conditions, stemming from graphene's extremely small effective electron mass.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-p01] Graphene's band gap can be tuned from 0 to 0.25 eV (about 5-micrometer wavelength) by applying a voltage to a dual-gate bilayer graphene field-effect transistor (FET) at room temperature.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-p01] The optical response of graphene nanoribbons is tunable into the terahertz regime by an applied magnetic fields.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-p01] Graphene/graphene oxide systems exhibit electrochromic behavior, enabling tuning of both linear and ultrafast optical properties.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-p01] A graphene-based Bragg grating (one-dimensional photonic crystal) has been fabricated, demonstrating its capability to excite surface electromagnetic waves in periodic structure using a 633 nm (6.33×10−7 m) He–Ne laser as the light source.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-p01] Graphene exhibits unique saturable absorption, which saturates when the input optical intensity exceeds a threshold value.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-p01] This nonlinear optical behavior, termed saturable absorption, occurs across the visible to near-infrared spectrum, due to graphene's universal optical absorption and zero band gap.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-p01] This property has enabled full-band mode-locking in fiber lasers using graphene-based saturable absorbers, contributing significantly to ultrafast photonics.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-p01] Additionally, the optical response of graphene/graphene oxide layers can be electrically tuned.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-p01] Saturable absorption in graphene could occur at the Microwave and Terahertz band, owing to its wideband optical absorption property.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-p01] The microwave-saturable absorption in graphene demonstrates the possibility of graphene microwaves and terahertz photonics devices, such as a microwave-saturable absorber, modulator, polarizer, microwave signal processing, and broadband wireless access networks.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-p01] Under intense laser illumination, graphene exhibits a nonlinear phase shift due to the optical nonlinear Kerr effect.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-p01] Graphene demonstrates a large nonlinear Kerr coefficient of 10−7 cm2⋅W−1, nearly nine orders of magnitude larger than that of bulk dielectrics, suggesting its potential as a powerful nonlinear Kerr medium capable of supporting various nonlinear effects, including solitons.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-p01] First-principle calculations incorporating quasiparticle corrections and many-body effects have been employed to study the electronic and optical properties of graphene-based materials.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-p01] The approach was described as three stages.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-p01] Graphene is considered an ideal material for spintronics due to its minimal spin–orbit interaction, the near absence of nuclear magnetic moments in carbon, and weak hyperfine interaction.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-p01] Electrical injection and detection of spin current have been demonstrated up to room temperature, with spin coherence length exceeding 1 micrometer observed at this temperature.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-p01] Control of spin current polarity via electrical gating has been achieved at low temperatures.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-p01] Graphene's quantum Hall effect in magnetic fields above approximately 10 tesla reveals additional interesting features.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-p01] Additional plateaus in Hall conductivity at $\sigma _{xy}=\nu e^{2}/h$ with $\nu =0,\pm {1},\pm {4}$ have been observed, along with plateau at $\nu =3$ and a fractional quantum Hall effect at $\nu =1/3$ .
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-p01] These observations with $\nu =0,\pm 1,\pm 3,\pm 4$ indicate that the four-fold degeneracy (two valley and two spin degrees of freedom) of the Landau energy levels is partially or completely lifted.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-p01] One hypothesis proposes that magnetic catalysis of symmetry breaking is responsible for this degeneracy lift.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-p01] Graphene exhibits spintronic and magnetic properties concurrently.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-p01] Low-defect graphene Nano-meshes, fabricated using a non-lithographic approach, exhibit significant ferromagnetism even at room temperature.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-p01] Additionally, a spin pumping effect has been observed with fields applied in parallel to the planes of few-layer ferromagnetic nano-meshes, while a magnetoresistance hysteresis loop is evident under perpendicular fields.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-p01] Charge-neutral graphene has demonstrated magnetoresistance exceeding 100% in magnetic fields generated by standard permanent magnets (approximately 0.1 tesla), marking a record magneto resistivity *at room temperature* among known materials.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-p01] In 2010, researchers magnetized graphene by producing it via CVD on the Ni(111) substrate and then in 2014 by placing it on an atomically smooth layer of magnetic yttrium iron garnet, maintaining graphene's electronic properties unaffected.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-p01] Previous methods involved doping graphene with other substances.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-p01] The dopant's presence negatively affected its electronic properties.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-p01] As noted above, the (two-dimensional) density of graphene is 0.762 mg per square meter.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-p01] Graphene is the strongest material ever tested, with an intrinsic tensile strength of 130 GPa (19,000,000 psi) (with representative engineering tensile strength ~50-60 GPa for stretching large-area freestanding graphene) and a Young's modulus (stiffness) close to 1 TPa (150,000,000 psi).
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-p01] The Nobel announcement illustrated this by saying that a 1 square meter graphene hammock would support a 4 kg cat but would weigh only as much as one of the cat's whiskers, at 0.77 mg (about 0.001% of the weight of 1 m2 of paper).
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-p01] Large-angle bending of graphene monolayers with minimal strain demonstrates its mechanical robustness.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-p01] Even under extreme deformation, monolayer graphene maintains excellent carrier mobility.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-p01] The spring constant of suspended graphene sheets has been measured using an atomic force microscope (AFM).
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-p01] Graphene sheets were suspended over SiO 2 cavities where an AFM tip was used to apply stress to the sheet to test its mechanical properties.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-p01] Its spring constant was in the range 1–5 N/m and the stiffness was 0.5 TPa, which differs from that of bulk graphite.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-p01] These intrinsic properties could lead to applications such as NEMS as pressure sensors and resonators.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-p01] Due to its large surface energy and out of plane ductility, flat graphene sheets are unstable with respect to scrolling, i.e. bending into a cylindrical shape, which is its lower-energy state.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-p01] In two-dimensional structures like graphene, thermal and quantum fluctuations cause relative displacement, with fluctuations growing logarithmically with structure size as per the Mermin–Wagner theorem.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-p01] This shows that the amplitude of long-wavelength fluctuations grows logarithmically with the scale of a 2D structure, and would therefore be unbounded in structures of infinite size.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-p01] Local deformation and elastic strain are negligibly affected by this long-range divergence in relative displacement.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-p01] It is believed that a sufficiently large 2D structure, in the absence of applied lateral tension, will bend and crumple to form a fluctuating 3D structure.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-p01] Researchers have observed ripples in suspended layers of graphene, and it has been proposed that the ripples are caused by thermal fluctuations in the material.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-p01] As a consequence of these dynamical deformations, it is debatable whether graphene is truly a 2D structure.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-p01] These ripples, when amplified by vacancy defects, induce a negative Poisson's ratio into graphene, resulting in the thinnest auxetic material known so far.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-p01] Graphene-nickel (Ni) composites, created through plating processes, exhibit enhanced mechanical properties due to strong Ni-graphene interactions inhibiting dislocation sliding in the Ni matrix.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-p01] In 2014, researchers from Rice University and the Georgia Institute of Technology have indicated that despite its strength, graphene is also relatively brittle, with a fracture toughness of about 4 MPa√m.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-p01] This indicates that imperfect graphene is likely to crack in a brittle manner like ceramic materials, as opposed to many metallic materials which tend to have fracture toughness in the range of 15–50 MPa√m.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-p01] Later in 2014, the Rice team announced that graphene showed a greater ability to distribute force from an impact than any known material, ten times that of steel per unit weight.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-p01] The force was transmitted at 22.2 kilometres per second (13.8 mi/s).
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-p01] Various methods – most notably, chemical vapor deposition (CVD), as discussed in the section below – have been developed to produce large-scale graphene needed for device applications.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-p01] Such methods often synthesize polycrystalline graphene.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-p01] The mechanical properties of polycrystalline graphene are affected by the nature of the defects, such as grain-boundaries (GB) and vacancies, present in the system and the average grain-size.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-p01] Graphene grain boundaries typically contain heptagon-pentagon pairs.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-p01] The arrangement of such defects depends on whether the GB is in a zig-zag or armchair direction.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-p01] It further depends on the tilt-angle of the GB.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-p01] In 2010, researchers from Brown University computationally predicted that as the tilt-angle increases, the grain boundary strength also increases.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-p01] They showed that the weakest link in the grain boundary is at the critical bonds of the heptagon rings.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-p01] As the grain boundary angle increases, the strain in these heptagon rings decreases, causing the grain boundary to be stronger than lower-angle GBs.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-p01] They proposed that, in fact, for sufficiently large angle GB, the strength of the GB is similar to pristine graphene.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-p01] In 2012, it was further shown that the strength can increase or decrease, depending on the detailed arrangements of the defects.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-p01] These predictions have since been supported by experimental evidence.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-p01] In a 2013 study led by James Hone's group, researchers probed the elastic stiffness and strength of CVD-grown graphene by combining nano-indentation and high-resolution TEM.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-p01] They found that the elastic stiffness is identical and strength is only slightly lower than those in pristine graphene.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-p01] In the same year, researchers from University of California, Berkeley and University of California, Los Angeles probed bi-crystalline graphene with TEM and AFM.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-p01] They found that the strength of grain boundaries indeed tends to increase with the tilt angle.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-p01] While the presence of vacancies is not only prevalent in polycrystalline graphene, vacancies can have significant effects on the strength of graphene.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-p01] The consensus is that the strength decreases along with increasing densities of vacancies.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-p01] Various studies have shown that for graphene with a sufficiently low density of vacancies, the strength does not vary significantly from that of pristine graphene.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-p01] On the other hand, a high density of vacancies can severely reduce the strength of graphene.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-p01] Compared to the fairly well-understood nature of the effect that grain boundary and vacancies have on the mechanical properties of graphene, there is no clear consensus on the general effect that the average grain size has on the strength of polycrystalline graphene.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-p01] In fact, three notable theoretical or computational studies on this topic have led to three different conclusions.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-p01] First, in 2012, Kolakowski and Myer studied the mechanical properties of polycrystalline graphene with "realistic atomistic model", using molecular-dynamics (MD) simulation.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-p01] To emulate the growth mechanism of CVD, they first randomly selected nucleation sites that are at least 5A (arbitrarily chosen) apart from other sites.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-p01] Polycrystalline graphene was generated from these nucleation sites and was subsequently annealed at 3000K, and then quenched.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-p01] Based on this model, they found that cracks are initiated at grain-boundary junctions, but the grain size does not significantly affect the strength.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-p01] Song et al. used MD simulations to study the mechanical properties of polycrystalline graphene with uniform-sized hexagon-shaped grains.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-p01] The hexagon grains were oriented in various lattice directions and the GBs consisted of only heptagon, pentagon, and hexagonal carbon rings.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-p01] The motivation behind such a model was that similar systems had been experimentally observed in graphene flakes grown on the surface of liquid copper.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-p01] While they also noted that crack is typically initiated at the triple junctions, they found that as the grain size decreases, the yield strength of graphene increases.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-p01] Based on this finding, they proposed that polycrystalline follows pseudo Hall-Petch relationship.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-p01] Sha et al. studied the effect of grain size on the properties of polycrystalline graphene, by modeling the grain patches using Voronoi construction.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-p01] The GBs in this model consisted of heptagons, pentagons, and hexagons, as well as squares, octagons, and vacancies.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-p01] Through MD simulation, contrary to the aforementioned study, they found an inverse Hall-Petch relationship, where the strength of graphene increases as the grain size increases.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-p01] Experimental observations and other theoretical predictions also gave differing conclusions, similar to the three given above.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-p01] Such discrepancies show the complexity of the effects that grain size, arrangements of defects, and the nature of defects have on the mechanical properties of polycrystalline graphene.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-p02] Thermal transport in graphene is a burgeoning area of research, particularly for its potential applications in thermal management.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-p02] Most experimental measurements have posted large uncertainties in the results of thermal conductivity due to the limitations of the instruments used.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-p02] The large range in the reported thermal conductivity can be caused by large measurement uncertainties as well as variations in the graphene quality and processing conditions.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-p02] Likewise, polymeric residue can contribute to a similar decrease in the thermal conductivity of suspended graphene to approximately 500 – 600 W⋅m−1⋅K−1 for bilayer graphene.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-p02] Isotopic composition, specifically the ratio of 12C to 13C, significantly affects graphene's thermal conductivity.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-p02] Isotopically pure 12C graphene exhibits higher thermal conductivity than either a 50:50 isotope ratio or the naturally occurring 99:1 ratio.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-p02] It can be shown by using the Wiedemann–Franz law, that the thermal conduction is phonon-dominated.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-p02] However, for a gated graphene strip, an applied gate bias causing a Fermi energy shift much larger than *k*B*T* can cause the electronic contribution to increase and dominate over the phonon contribution at low temperatures.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-p02] The ballistic thermal conductance of graphene is isotropic.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-p02] In addition, the ballistic thermal conductance of graphene is shown to give the lower limit of the ballistic thermal conductance, per unit circumference, length of carbon nanotubes.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-p02] Graphene's thermal conductivity is influenced by its three acoustic phonon modes: two linear dispersion relation dispersion relation in-plane modes (LA, TA) and one quadratic dispersion relation out-of-plane mode (ZA).
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-p02] At low temperatures, the dominance of the T1.5 thermal conductivity contribution of the out-of-plane mode supersedes the *T*2 dependence of the linear modes.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-p02] Some graphene phonon bands exhibit negative Grüneisen parameters, resulting in negative thermal expansion coefficient at low temperatures.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-p02] The lowest negative Grüneisen parameters correspond to the lowest transverse acoustic ZA modes, whose frequencies increase with in-plane lattice parameter, akin to a stretched string with higher frequency vibrations.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-p02] Graphene has a theoretical specific surface area (SSA) of 2630 m2/g.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-p02] This is much larger than that reported to date for carbon black (typically smaller than 900 m2/g) or for carbon nanotubes (CNTs), from ≈100 to 1000 m2/g and is similar to activated carbon.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-p02] Graphene is the only form of carbon (or solid material) in which every atom is available for chemical reaction from two sides (due to the 2D structure).
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-p02] Atoms at the edges of a graphene sheet have special chemical reactivity.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-p02] Graphene has the highest ratio of edge atoms of any allotrope.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-p02] Defects within a sheet increase its chemical reactivity.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-p02] The onset temperature of reaction between the basal plane of single-layer graphene and oxygen gas is below 260 °C (530 K).
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-p02] Graphene burns at very low temperatures (e.g., 350 °C (620 K)).
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-p02] Graphene is commonly modified with oxygen- and nitrogen-containing functional groups and analyzed by infrared spectroscopy and X-ray photoelectron spectroscopy.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-p02] However, the determination of structures of graphene with oxygen- and nitrogen- functional groups require the structures to be well controlled.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-p02] In 2013, Stanford University physicists reported that single-layer graphene is a hundred times more chemically reactive than thicker multilayer sheets.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-p02] Graphene can self-repair holes in its sheets, when exposed to molecules containing carbon, such as hydrocarbons.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-p02] Bombarded with pure carbon atoms, the atoms perfectly align into hexagons, filling the holes.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-p02] Despite the promising results in different cell studies and proof of concept studies, there is still incomplete understanding of the full biocompatibility of graphene-based materials.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-p02] Different cell lines react differently when exposed to graphene, and it has been shown that the lateral size of the graphene flakes, the form and surface chemistry can elicit different biological responses on the same cell line.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-p02] There are indications that graphene has promise as a useful material for interacting with neural cells; studies on cultured neural cells show limited success.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-p02] Graphene also has some utility in osteogenesis.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-p02] Researchers at the Graphene Research Centre at the National University of Singapore (NUS) discovered in 2011 the ability of graphene to accelerate the osteogenic differentiation of human mesenchymal stem cells without the use of biochemical inducers.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-p02] Graphene can be used in biosensors; in 2015, researchers demonstrated that a graphene-based sensor can be used to detect a cancer risk biomarker.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-p02] In particular, by using epitaxial graphene on silicon carbide, they were repeatedly able to detect 8-hydroxydeoxyguanosine (8-OHdG), a DNA damage biomarker.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-p02] The electronic property of graphene can be significantly influenced by the supporting substrate.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-p02] Studies of graphene monolayers on clean and hydrogen(H)-passivated silicon (100) (Si(100)/H) surfaces have been performed.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-p02] The Si(100)/H surface does not perturb the electronic properties of graphene, whereas the interaction between the clean Si(100) surface and graphene changes the electronic states of graphene significantly.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-p02] This effect results from the covalent bonding between C and surface Si atoms, modifying the π-orbital network of the graphene layer.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-p02] The local density of states shows that the bonded C and Si surface states are highly disturbed near the Fermi energy.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-p02] In 2013 a group of Polish scientists presented a production unit that allows the manufacture of continuous monolayer sheets.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-p02] The process is based on graphene growth on a liquid metal matrix.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-p02] The product of this process was called High Strength Metallurgical Graphene.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-p02] In a new study published in Nature, the researchers have used a single-layer graphene electrode and a novel surface-sensitive non-linear spectroscopy technique to investigate the top-most water layer at the electrochemically charged surface.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-p02] They found that the interfacial water response to the applied electric field is asymmetric concerning the nature of the applied field.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-p02] Bilayer graphene displays the anomalous quantum Hall effect, a tunable band gap and potential for excitonic condensation –making it a promising candidate for optoelectronic and nanoelectronic applications.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-p02] Bilayer graphene typically can be found either in twisted configurations where the two layers are rotated relative to each other or graphitic Bernal stacked configurations where half the atoms in one layer lie atop half the atoms in the other.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-p02] Stacking order and orientation govern the optical and electronic properties of bilayer graphene.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-p02] One way to synthesize bilayer graphene is via chemical vapor deposition, which can produce large bilayer regions that almost exclusively conform to a Bernal stack geometry.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-p02] It has been shown that the two graphene layers can withstand important strain or doping mismatch which ultimately should lead to their exfoliation.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-p02] Turbostratic graphene exhibits weak interlayer coupling, and the spacing is increased with respect to Bernal-stacked multilayer graphene.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-p02] Rotational misalignment preserves the 2D electronic structure, as confirmed by Raman spectroscopy.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-p02] The D peak is very weak, whereas the 2D and G peaks remain prominent.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-p02] A rather peculiar feature is that the I2D/IG ratio can exceed 10.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-p02] However, most importantly, the M peak, which originates from AB stacking, is absent, whereas the TS1 and TS2 modes are visible in the Raman spectrum.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-p02] The material is formed through conversion of non-graphenic carbon into graphenic carbon without providing sufficient energy to allow for the reorganization through annealing of adjacent graphene layers into crystalline graphitic structures.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-p02] Periodically stacked graphene and its insulating isomorph provide a fascinating structural element in implementing highly functional superlattices at the atomic scale, which offers possibilities for designing nanoelectronic and photonic devices.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-p02] Various types of superlattices can be obtained by stacking graphene and its related forms.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-p02] The energy band in layer-stacked superlattices is found to be more sensitive to the barrier width than that in conventional III–V semiconductor superlattices.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-p02] When adding more than one atomic layer to the barrier in each period, the coupling of electronic wavefunctions in neighboring potential wells can be significantly reduced, which leads to the degeneration of continuous subbands into quantized energy levels.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-p02] When varying the well width, the energy levels in the potential wells along the L-M direction behave distinctly from those along the K-H direction.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-p02] A superlattice corresponds to a periodic or quasi-periodic arrangement of different materials and can be described by a superlattice period which confers a new translational symmetry to the system, impacting their phonon dispersions and subsequently their thermal transport properties.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-p02] Recently, uniform monolayer graphene-hBN structures have been successfully synthesized via lithography patterning coupled with chemical vapor deposition (CVD).
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-p02] Furthermore, superlattices of graphene-HBN are ideal model systems for the realization and understanding of coherent (wave-like) and incoherent (particle-like) phonon thermal transport.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-p02] Graphene nanoribbons ("nanostripes" in the "zig-zag"/"zigzag" orientation), at low temperatures, show spin-polarized metallic edge currents, which also suggests applications in the new field of spintronics.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-p02] A graphene quantum dot (GQD) is a graphene fragment with a size less than 100 nm.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-p02] The properties of GQDs are different from bulk graphene due to the quantum confinement effects which only become apparent when the size is smaller than 100 nm.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-p02] Graphene oxide is usually produced through chemical exfoliation of graphite.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-p02] A particularly popular technique is the improved Hummers' method.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-p02] Using paper-making techniques on dispersed, oxidized and chemically processed graphite in water, the monolayer flakes form a single sheet and create strong bonds.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-p02] These sheets, called graphene oxide paper, have a measured tensile modulus of 32 GPa.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-p02] The chemical property of graphite oxide is related to the functional groups attached to graphene sheets.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-p02] These can change the polymerization pathway and similar chemical processes.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-p02] Graphene oxide flakes in polymers display enhanced photo-conducting properties.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-p02] Graphene is normally hydrophobic and impermeable to all gases and liquids (vacuum-tight).
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-p02] However, when formed into a graphene oxide-based capillary membrane, both liquid water and water vapor flow through as quickly as if the membrane were not present.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-p02] In 2022, researchers evaluated the biological effects of low doses on graphene oxide on larvae and imago of *Drosophila melanogaster*.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-p02] Results show that oral administration of graphene oxide at concentrations of 0.02-1% has a beneficial effect on the developmental rate and hatching ability of larvae.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-p02] Long-term administration of a low dose of graphene oxide extends the lifespan of Drosophila and significantly enhances resistance to environmental stresses.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-p02] These suggest that graphene oxide affects carbohydrate and lipid metabolism in adult Drosophila.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-p02] These findings might provide a useful reference to assess the biological effects of graphene oxide, which could play an important role in a variety of graphene-based biomedical applications.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-p02] Soluble fragments of graphene can be prepared in the laboratory through chemical modification of graphite.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-p02] First, microcrystalline graphite is treated with an acidic mixture of sulfuric acid and nitric acid.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-p02] A series of oxidation and exfoliation steps produce small graphene plates with carboxyl groups at their edges.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-p02] These are converted to acid chloride groups by treatment with thionyl chloride; next, they are converted to the corresponding graphene amide via treatment with octadecyl amine.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-p02] The resulting material (circular graphene layers of 5.3 Å or 5.3×10−10 m thickness) is soluble in tetrahydrofuran, tetrachloromethane and dichloroethane.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-p02] Refluxing single-layer graphene oxide (SLGO) in solvents leads to size reduction and folding of individual sheets as well as loss of carboxylic group functionality, by up to 20%, indicating thermal instabilities of SLGO sheets dependent on their preparation methodology.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-p02] When using thionyl chloride, acyl chloride groups result, which can then form aliphatic and aromatic amides with a reactivity conversion of around 70–80%.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-p02] Hydrazine reflux is commonly used for reducing SLGO to SLG(R), but titrations show that only around 20–30% of the carboxylic groups are lost, leaving a significant number available for chemical attachment.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-p02] Analysis of SLG(R) generated by this route reveals that the system is unstable and using a room temperature stirring with hydrochloric acid (< 1.0 M) leads to around 60% loss of COOH functionality.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-p02] Room temperature treatment of SLGO with carbodiimides leads to the collapse of the individual sheets into star-like clusters that exhibited poor subsequent reactivity with amines (c.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-p02] 3–5% conversion of the intermediate to the final amide).
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-p02] It is apparent that conventional chemical treatment of carboxylic groups on SLGO generates morphological changes of individual sheets that leads to a reduction in chemical reactivity, which may potentially limit their use in composite synthesis.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-p02] Therefore, chemical reaction types have been explored.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-p02] SLGO has also been grafted with polyallylamine, cross-linked through epoxy groups.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-p02] When filtered into graphene oxide paper, these composites exhibit increased stiffness and strength relative to unmodified graphene oxide paper.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-p02] Full hydrogenation from both sides of the graphene sheet results in Graphane, but partial hydrogenation leads to hydrogenated graphene.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-p02] Similarly, both-side fluorination of graphene (or chemical and mechanical exfoliation of graphite fluoride) leads to fluorographene (graphene fluoride), while partial fluorination (generally halogenation) provides fluorinated (halogenated) graphene.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-p02] Graphene can be a ligand to coordinate metals and metal ions by introducing functional groups.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-p02] Structures of graphene ligands are similar to e.g. metal-porphyrin complex, metal-phthalocyanine complex, and metal-phenanthroline complex.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-p02] Copper and nickel ions can be coordinated with graphene ligands.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-p02] In 2011, researchers reported a novel yet simple approach to fabricating graphene fibers from chemical vapor deposition-grown graphene films.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-p02] The method was scalable and controllable, delivering tunable morphology and pore structure by controlling the evaporation of solvents with suitable surface tension.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-p02] Flexible all-solid-state supercapacitors based on these graphene fibers were demonstrated in 2013.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-p02] In 2015, intercalating small graphene fragments into the gaps formed by larger, coiled graphene sheets, after annealing provided pathways for conduction, while the fragments helped reinforce the fibers.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-p02] The resulting fibers offered better thermal and electrical conductivity and mechanical strength.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-p02] Thermal conductivity reached 1,290 W/m/K (1,290 watts per metre per kelvin), while tensile strength reached 1,080 MPa (157,000 psi).
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-p02] In 2016, kilometer-scale continuous graphene fibers with outstanding mechanical properties and excellent electrical conductivity were produced by high-throughput wet-spinning of graphene oxide liquid crystals followed by graphitization through a full-scale synergetic defect-engineering strategy.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-p02] The graphene fibers with superior performances promise wide applications in functional textiles, lightweight motors, microelectronic devices, etc.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-p02] Tsinghua University in Beijing, led by Wei Fei of the Department of Chemical Engineering, claims to be able to create a carbon nanotube fiber that has a tensile strength of 80 GPa (12,000,000 psi).
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-p02] In 2013, a three-dimensional honeycomb of hexagonally arranged carbon was termed 3D graphene, and self-supporting 3D graphene was also produced.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-p02] 3D structures of graphene can be fabricated by using either CVD or solution-based methods.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-p02] A 2016 review by Khurram and Xu et al. provided a summary of then-state-of-the-art techniques for fabrication of the 3D structure of graphene and other related two-dimensional materials.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-p02] In 2013, researchers at Stony Brook University reported a novel radical-initiated crosslinking method to fabricate porous 3D free-standing architectures of graphene and carbon nanotubes using nanomaterials as building blocks without any polymer matrix as support.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-p02] These 3D graphenes (all-carbon) scaffolds/foams have applications in several fields such as energy storage, filtration, thermal management, and biomedical devices and implants.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-p02] Box-shaped graphene (BSG) nanostructure appearing after mechanical cleavage of pyrolytic graphite was reported in 2016.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-p02] The discovered nanostructure is a multilayer system of parallel hollow nanochannels located along the surface and having quadrangular cross-section.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-p02] The thickness of the channel walls is approximately equal to 1 nm.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-p02] Three dimensional bilayer graphene has also been reported.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-p02] Pillared graphene is a hybrid carbon structure, consisting of an oriented array of carbon nanotubes connected at each end to a sheet of graphene.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-p02] It was first described theoretically by George Froudakis and colleagues at the University of Crete in Greece in 2008.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-p02] Pillared graphene has not yet been synthesized in the laboratory, but it has been suggested that it may have useful electronic properties, or as a hydrogen storage material.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-p02] Graphene reinforced with embedded carbon nanotube reinforcing bars ("rebar") is easier to manipulate, while improving the electrical and mechanical qualities of both materials.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-p02] Functionalized single- or multi-walled carbon nanotubes are spin-coated on copper foils and then heated and cooled, using the nanotubes themselves as the carbon source.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-p02] Under heating, the functional carbon groups decompose into graphene, while the nanotubes partially split and form in-plane covalent bonds with the graphene, adding strength. π–π stacking domains add more strength.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-p02] The nanotubes can overlap, making the material a better conductor than standard CVD-grown graphene.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-p02] The nanotubes effectively bridge the grain boundaries found in conventional graphene.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-p02] The technique eliminates the traces of substrate on which later-separated sheets were deposited using epitaxy.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-p02] Stacks of a few layers have been proposed as a cost-effective and physically flexible replacement for indium tin oxide (ITO) used in displays and photovoltaic cells.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-p02] In 2015, researchers from the University of Illinois at Urbana–Champaign (UIUC) developed a new approach for forming 3D shapes from flat, 2D sheets of graphene.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-p02] A film of graphene that had been soaked in solvent to make it swell and become malleable was overlaid on an underlying substrate "former".
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-p02] The solvent evaporated over time, leaving behind a layer of graphene that had taken on the shape of the underlying structure.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-p02] In this way, they were able to produce a range of relatively intricate micro-structured shapes.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-p02] Pure graphene and gold-decorated graphene were each successfully integrated with the substrate.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-p02] An aerogel made of graphene layers separated by carbon nanotubes was measured at 0.16 milligrams per cubic centimeter.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-p02] A solution of graphene and carbon nanotubes in a mold is freeze-dried to dehydrate the solution, leaving the aerogel.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-p02] The material has superior elasticity and absorption.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-p02] It can recover completely after more than 90% compression, and absorb up to 900 times its weight in oil, at a rate of 68.8 grams per second.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-p02] In 2015, a coiled form of graphene was discovered in graphitic carbon (coal).
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-p02] The spiraling effect is produced by defects in the material's hexagonal grid that causes it to spiral along its edge, mimicking a Riemann surface, with the graphene surface approximately perpendicular to the axis.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-p02] When voltage is applied to such a coil, current flows around the spiral, producing a magnetic field.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-p02] The phenomenon applies to spirals with either zigzag or armchair patterns, although with different current distributions.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-p02] Computer simulations indicated that a conventional spiral inductor of 205 microns in diameter could be matched by a nanocoil just 70 nanometers wide, with a field strength reaching as much as 1 tesla.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-p02] The nano-solenoids analyzed through computer models at Rice University should be capable of producing powerful magnetic fields of about 1 tesla, about the same as the coils found in typical loudspeakers, according to Yakobson and his team – and about the same field strength as some MRI machines.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-p02] They found the magnetic field would be strongest in the hollow, nanometer-wide cavity at the spiral's center.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-p02] A solenoid made with such a coil behaves as a quantum conductor whose current distribution between the core and exterior varies with applied voltage, resulting in nonlinear inductance.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-p02] In 2016, Brown University introduced a method for "crumpling" graphene, adding wrinkles to the material on a nanoscale.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-p02] This was achieved by depositing layers of graphene oxide onto a shrink film, then shrunken, with the film dissolved before being shrunken again on another sheet of film.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-p02] The crumpled graphene became superhydrophobic, and when used as a battery electrode, the material was shown to have as much as a 400% increase in electrochemical current density.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-p02] A rapidly increasing list of production techniques have been developed to enable graphene's use in commercial applications.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-p02] Isolated 2D crystals cannot be grown via chemical synthesis beyond small sizes even in principle, because the rapid growth of phonon density with increasing lateral size forces 2D crystallites to bend into the third dimension.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-p02] In all cases, graphene must bond to a substrate to retain its two-dimensional shape.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-p02] Small graphene structures, such as graphene quantum dots and nanoribbons, can be produced by "bottom-up" methods that assemble the lattice from organic molecule monomers (e. g. citric acid, glucose).
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-p02] "Top-down" methods, on the other hand, cut bulk graphite and graphene materials with strong chemicals (e. g. mixed acids).
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-p02] Other methods do exist like exfoliation.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-p02] Geim and Novoselov initially used adhesive tape to pull graphene sheets away from graphite.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-p02] Achieving single layers typically requires multiple exfoliation steps.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-p02] After exfoliation, the flakes are deposited on a silicon wafer.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-p02] Crystallites larger than 1 mm and visible to the naked eye can be obtained.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-p02] As of 2014, exfoliation produced graphene with the lowest number of defects and highest electron mobility.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-p02] One specific exfoliation technique involved using a sharp single-crystal diamond wedge to penetrate the graphite source and precisely cleave individual layers.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-p02] That same year, researchers also developed liquid-phase methods, creating defect-free, unoxidized graphene-containing liquids from graphite using mixers that generate extremely high local shear rates greater than 10×104.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-p02] A 2014 study published in *Nature Materials* demonstrated that scalable production of defect-free graphene is possible through shear exfoliation using a high-shear mixer.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-p02] This technique can produce large quantities of few-layer graphene in solution while preserving structural integrity.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-p02] As turbulence is not necessary for mechanical exfoliation, resonant acoustic mixing or low-speed ball milling can also be effective in the production of high-yield and water-soluble graphene.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-p02] Liquid phase exfoliation (LPE) is a relatively simple method that involves dispersing graphite in a liquid medium to produce graphene by sonication or high shear mixing, followed by centrifugation.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-p02] Restacking is an issue with this technique unless solvents with appropriate surface energy are used (e.g.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-p02] Adding a surfactant to a solvent prior to sonication prevents restacking by adsorbing to the graphene's surface.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-p02] This produces a higher graphene concentration, but removing the surfactant requires chemical treatments.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-p02] LPE results in nanosheets with a broad size distribution and thicknesses roughly in the range of 1-10 monolayers.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-p02] However, liquid cascade centrifugation can be used to size-select the suspensions and achieve monolayer enrichment.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-p02] Sonicating graphite at the interface of two immiscible liquids, most notably heptane and water, produced macro-scale graphene films.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-p02] The graphene sheets are adsorbed to the high-energy interface between the materials and are kept from restacking.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-p02] The sheets are up to about 95% transparent and conductive.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-p02] With definite cleavage parameters, the box-shaped graphene (BSG) nanostructure can be prepared on graphite crystal.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-p02] A major advantage of LPE is that it can be used to exfoliate many inorganic 2D materials beyond graphene, e.g.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-p02] Liquid-phase exfoliation can also be done by a less-known process of intercalating supercritical carbon dioxide (scCO2) into the interstitial spaces in the graphite lattice, followed by rapid depressurization.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-p02] The scCO2 intercalates easily inside the graphite lattice at a pressure of roughly 100 atm.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-p02] Carbon dioxide turns gaseous as soon as the vessel is depressurized and makes the graphite explode into few-layered graphene.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-p02] This method may have multiple advantages: being non-toxic, the graphite does not have to be chemically treated in any way before the process, and the whole process can be completed in a single step as opposed to other exfoliation methods.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-p02] Graphene can be created by opening carbon nanotubes by cutting or etching.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-p02] In one such method, multi-walled carbon nanotubes were cut open in solution by action of potassium permanganate and sulfuric acid.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-p02] In 2014, carbon nanotube-reinforced graphene was made via spin coating and annealing functionalized carbon nanotubes.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-p02] Another approach sprays buckyballs at supersonic speeds onto a substrate.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-p02] The balls cracked open upon impact, and the resulting unzipped cages then bond together to form a graphene film.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-p02] Boehm reported producing monolayer flakes of reduced graphene oxide in 1962.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-p02] Rapid heating of graphite oxide and exfoliation yields highly dispersed carbon powder with a few percent of graphene flakes.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-p02] Another method is the reduction of graphite oxide monolayer films, e.g. by hydrazine with annealing in argon/hydrogen with an almost intact carbon framework that allows efficient removal of functional groups.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-p02] Measured charge carrier mobility exceeded 1,000 cm/Vs (10 m/Vs).
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-p02] Burning a graphite oxide coated DVD produced a conductive graphene film (1,738 siemens per meter) and specific surface area (1,520 square meters per gram) that was highly resistant and malleable.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-p02] A dispersed reduced graphene oxide suspension was synthesized in water by a hydrothermal dehydration method without using any surfactant.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-p02] The approach is facile, industrially applicable, environmentally friendly, and cost-effective.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-p02] Viscosity measurements confirmed that the graphene colloidal suspension (graphene nanofluid) exhibits Newtonian behavior, with the viscosity showing a close resemblance to that of water.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-p02] Graphite particles can be corroded in molten salts to form a variety of carbon nanostructures including graphene.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-p02] Hydrogen cations, dissolved in molten lithium chloride, can be discharged on cathodically polarized graphite rods, which then intercalate, peeling graphene sheets.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-p02] The graphene nanosheets produced displayed a single-crystalline structure with a lateral size of several hundred nanometers and a high degree of crystallinity and thermal stability.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-p02] Electrochemical synthesis can exfoliate graphene.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-p02] Varying a pulsed voltage controls thickness, flake area, and number of defects and affects its properties.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-p02] The process begins by bathing the graphite in a solvent for intercalation.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-p02] The process can be tracked by monitoring the solution's transparency with an LED and photodiode.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-p02] Graphene has been prepared by using a sugar like glucose, fructose, etc.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-p02] This substrate-free "bottom-up" synthesis is safer, simpler and more environmentally friendly than exfoliation.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-p02] The method can control the thickness, ranging from monolayer to multilayer, which is known as the "Tang-Lau Method".
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-p02] Gram-quantities were produced by the reaction of ethanol with sodium metal, followed by pyrolysis and washing with water.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-p02] In 2012, microwave energy was reported to directly synthesize graphene in one step.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-p02] This approach avoids use of potassium permanganate in the reaction mixture.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-p02] It was also reported that by microwave radiation assistance, graphene oxide with or without holes can be synthesized by controlling microwave time.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-p02] Microwave heating can dramatically shorten the reaction time from days to seconds.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-p02] Graphene can also be made by microwave assisted hydrothermal pyrolysis.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-p02] Heating silicon carbide (SiC) to high temperatures (1100 °C) under low pressures (c.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-p02] 10−6 torr, or 10−4 Pa) reduces it to graphene.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-p02] Epitaxial graphene growth on silicon carbide is a wafer-scale technique to produce graphene.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-p02] Epitaxial graphene may be coupled to surfaces weakly enough (by the active valence electrons that create Van der Waals forces) to retain the two-dimensional electronic band structure of isolated graphene.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-p02] A normal silicon wafer coated with a layer of germanium (Ge) dipped in dilute hydrofluoric acid strips the naturally forming germanium oxide groups, creating hydrogen-terminated germanium.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-p02] The direct synthesis of graphene on insulator TiO2 with high-dielectric-constant (high-κ).
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-p02] A two-step CVD process is shown to grow graphene directly on TiO2 crystals or exfoliated TiO2 nanosheets without using any metal catalyst.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-p02] CVD graphene can be grown on metal substrates including ruthenium, iridium, nickel and copper.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-p02] In 2014, a two-step roll-to-roll manufacturing process was announced.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-p02] The first roll-to-roll step produces the graphene via chemical vapor deposition.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-p02] The second step binds the graphene to a substrate.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-p02] Growing graphene in an industrial resistive-heating cold wall CVD system was claimed to produce graphene 100 times faster than conventional CVD systems, cut costs by 99%, and produce material with enhanced electronic qualities.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-p02] CVD graphene is scalable and has been grown on deposited Cu thin film catalyst on 100 to 300 mm standard Si/SiO2 wafers on an Axitron Black Magic system.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-p02] Monolayer graphene coverage of >95% is achieved on 100 to 300 mm wafer substrates with negligible defects, confirmed by extensive Raman mapping.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-p02] Adamson, graphene can be produced from natural graphite while preserving the integrity of the sheets using the solvent interface trapping method (SITM).
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-p02] SITM uses a high-energy interface, such as oil and water, to exfoliate graphite to graphene.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-p02] Stacked graphite delaminates, or spreads, at the oil/water interface to produce few-layer graphene in a thermodynamically favorable process in much the same way as small molecule surfactants spread to minimize the interfacial energy.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-p02] In this way, graphene behaves like a 2D surfactant.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-p02] SITM has been reported for a variety of applications such conductive polymer-graphene foams, conductive polymer-graphene microspheres, conductive thin films and conductive inks.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-p02] A highly exothermic reaction combusts magnesium in an oxidation-reduction reaction with carbon dioxide, producing carbon nanoparticles including graphene and fullerenes.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-p02] Supersonic acceleration of droplets through a Laval nozzle was used to deposit reduced graphene oxide on a substrate.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-p02] The energy of the impact rearranges those carbon atoms into flawless graphene.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-p02] In 2014, a CO 2 infrared laser was used to produce patterned porous three-dimensional laser-induced graphene (LIG) film networks from commercial polymer films.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-p02] The resulting material exhibits high electrical conductivity and surface area.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-p02] The laser induction process is compatible with roll-to-roll manufacturing processes.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-p02] A similar material, laser-induced graphene fibers (LIGF), was reported in 2018.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-p02] In 2019, flash Joule heating (transient high-temperature electrothermal heating) was discovered to be a method to synthesize turbostratic graphene in bulk powder form.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-p02] The method involves electrothermally converting various carbon sources, such as carbon black, coal, and food waste into micron-scale flakes of graphene.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-p02] More recent works demonstrated the use of mixed plastic waste, waste rubber tires, and pyrolysis ash as carbon feedstocks.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-p02] The graphenization process is kinetically controlled, and the energy dose is chosen to preserve the carbon in its graphenic state (excessive energy input leads to subsequent graphitization through annealing).
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-p02] Accelerating carbon ions inside an electrical field into a semiconductor made of thin nickel films on a substrate of SiO2/Si, creates a wafer-scale (4 inches (100 mm)) wrinkle/tear/residue-free graphene layer at a relatively low temperature of 500 °C.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-p02] Integration of graphene in the widely employed CMOS fabrication process demands its transfer-free direct synthesis on dielectric substrates at temperatures below 500 °C.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-p02] At the IEDM 2018, researchers from University of California, Santa Barbara, demonstrated a novel CMOS-compatible graphene synthesis process at 300 °C suitable for back-end-of-line (BEOL) applications.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-p02] The process involves pressure-assisted solid-state diffusion of carbon through a thin-film of metal catalyst.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-p02] The synthesized large-area graphene films were shown to exhibit high quality (via Raman characterization) and similar resistivity values when compared with high-temperature CVD synthesized graphene films of the same cross-section down to widths of 20 nm.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-p02] In addition to experimental investigation of graphene and graphene-based devices, numerical modeling and simulation of graphene has also been an important research topic.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-p02] The Kubo formula provides an analytic expression for the graphene's conductivity and shows that it is a function of several physical parameters including wavelength, temperature, and chemical potential.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-p02] Moreover, a surface conductivity model, which describes graphene as an infinitesimally thin (two-sided) sheet with a local and isotropic conductivity, has been proposed.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-p02] This model permits the derivation of analytical expressions for the electromagnetic field in the presence of a graphene sheet in terms of a dyadic Green function (represented using Sommerfeld integrals) and exciting electric current.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-p02] Even though these analytical models and methods can provide results for several canonical problems for benchmarking purposes, many practical problems involving graphene, such as the design of arbitrarily shaped electromagnetic devices, are analytically intractable.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-p02] With the recent advances in the field of computational electromagnetics (CEM), various accurate and efficient numerical methods have become available for analysis of electromagnetic field/wave interactions on graphene sheets and/or graphene-based devices.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-p02] A comprehensive summary of computational tools developed for analyzing graphene-based devices/systems is proposed.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-p02] Graphene analogs (also referred to as "artificial graphene") are two-dimensional systems which exhibit similar properties to graphene.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-p02] Graphene analogs have been studied intensively since the discovery of graphene in 2004.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-p02] People try to develop systems in which the physics is easier to observe and manipulate than in graphene.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-p02] In those systems, electrons are not always the particles that are used.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-p02] They might be optical photons, microwave photons, plasmons, microcavity polaritons, or even atoms.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-p02] Also, the honeycomb structure in which those particles evolve can be of a different nature than carbon atoms in graphene.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-p02] It can be, respectively, a photonic crystal, an array of metallic rods, metallic nanoparticles, a lattice of coupled microcavities, or an optical lattice.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-p02] Graphene is a transparent and flexible conductor that holds great promise for various material/device applications, including solar cells, light-emitting diodes (LED), integrated photonic circuit devices, touch panels, and smart windows or phones.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-p02] Smartphone products with graphene touch screens are already on the market.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-p02] In 2013, Head announced their new range of graphene tennis racquets.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-p02] As of 2015, there is one product available for commercial use: a graphene-infused printer powder.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-p02] Many other uses for graphene have been proposed or are under development, in areas including electronics, biological engineering, filtration, lightweight/strong composite materials, photovoltaics and energy storage.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-p02] Graphene is often produced as a powder and as a dispersion in a polymer matrix.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-p02] This dispersion is supposedly suitable for advanced composites, paints and coatings, lubricants, oils and functional fluids, capacitors and batteries, thermal management applications, display materials and packaging, solar cells, inks and 3D-printer materials, and barriers and films.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-p02] On 2 August 2016, Briggs Automative Company's new Mono model is said to be made out of graphene as the first of both a street-legal track car and a production car.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-p02] In January 2018, graphene-based spiral inductors exploiting kinetic inductance at room temperature were first demonstrated at the University of California, Santa Barbara, led by Kaustav Banerjee.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-p02] These inductors were predicted to allow significant miniaturization in radio-frequency integrated circuit applications.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-p02] The potential of epitaxial graphene on SiC for metrology has been shown since 2010, displaying quantum Hall resistance quantization accuracy of three parts per billion in monolayer epitaxial graphene.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-p02] Over the years precisions of parts-per-trillion in the Hall resistance quantization and giant quantum Hall plateaus have been demonstrated.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-p02] Developments in the encapsulation and doping of epitaxial graphene have led to the commercialization of epitaxial graphene quantum resistance standards.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-p02] Novel uses for graphene continue to be researched and explored.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-p02] One such use is in combination with water-based epoxy resins to produce anticorrosive coatings.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-p02] The van der Waals nature of graphene and other two-dimensional (2D) materials also permits van der Waals heterostructures and integrated circuits based on Van der Waals integration of 2D materials.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-p02] Graphene is utilized in detecting gasses and chemicals in environmental monitoring, developing highly sensitive biosensors for medical diagnostics, and creating flexible, wearable sensors for health monitoring.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-p02] Graphene's transparency also enhances optical sensors, making them more effective in imaging and spectroscopy.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-p02] One review on graphene toxicity published in 2016 by Lalwani et al. summarizes the in vitro, in vivo, antimicrobial and environmental effects and highlights the various mechanisms of graphene toxicity.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-p02] Another review published in 2016 by Ou et al. focused on graphene-family nanomaterials (GFNs) and revealed several typical mechanisms such as physical destruction, oxidative stress, DNA damage, inflammatory response, apoptosis, autophagy, and necrosis.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-p02] A 2020 study showed that the toxicity of graphene is dependent on several factors such as shape, size, purity, post-production processing steps, oxidative state, functional groups, dispersion state, synthesis methods, route and dose of administration, and exposure times.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-p02] In 2014, research at Stony Brook University showed that graphene nanoribbons, graphene nanoplatelets, and graphene nano–onions are non-toxic at concentrations up to 50 μg/ml.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-p02] These nanoparticles do not alter the differentiation of human bone marrow stem cells towards osteoblasts (bone) or adipocytes (fat), suggesting that at low doses, graphene nanoparticles are safe for biomedical applications.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-p02] In 2013, research at Brown University found that 10 μm few-layered graphene flakes can pierce cell membranes in solution.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-p02] They were observed to enter initially via sharp and jagged points, allowing graphene to be internalized in the cell.
[src:graphene-materials/graphene-p02] The physiological effects of this remain unknown, and this remains a relatively unexplored field.
[src:graphene-materials/graphite] Graphite can occur naturally or be produced synthetically.
[src:graphene-materials/graphite] Natural graphite is obtained from naturally occurring geologic deposits and synthetic graphite is produced through human activity.
[src:graphene-materials/graphite] Graphite occurs naturally in ores that can be classified as either *amorphous* (microcrystalline) or *crystalline* (flake or lump/chip) which is determined by the ore morphology, crystallinity, and grain size.
[src:graphene-materials/graphite] All naturally occurring graphite deposits are formed from the metamorphism of carbonaceous sedimentary rocks, and the ore type is due to its geologic setting.
[src:graphene-materials/graphite] Coal that has been thermally metamorphosed is the typical source of amorphous graphite.
[src:graphene-materials/graphite] Crystalline flake graphite is mined from carbonaceous metamorphic rocks, while lump or chip graphite is mined from veins which occur in high-grade metamorphic regions.
[src:graphene-materials/graphite] There are serious negative environmental impacts to graphite mining.
[src:graphene-materials/graphite] Synthetic graphite has high purity and is usually produced by the thermal graphitization of hydrocarbon materials at temperatures in excess of 2,100 °C, most commonly through the Acheson process.
[src:graphene-materials/graphite] The high temperatures are maintained for weeks, and are required not only to form the graphite from the precursor carbons but also to vaporize any impurities that may be present, including hydrogen, nitrogen, sulfur, organics, and metals.
[src:graphene-materials/graphite] The resulting synthetic graphite is highly pure—in excess of 99.9% C purity—but typically has lower density, conductivity and a higher porosity than its natural equivalent.
[src:graphene-materials/graphite] Synthetic graphite can be formed into very large (centimeter-scale) flakes while maintaining its high purity, unlike almost all sources of natural graphite.
[src:graphene-materials/graphite] Synthetic graphite can also be formed by other methods including by chemical vapor deposition from hydrocarbons at temperatures above 2,500 K (2,230 °C), by decomposition of thermally unstable carbides, or by crystallization from metal melts supersaturated with carbon.
[src:graphene-materials/graphite] Research and development efforts continue into new methods for the industrial production of graphite for a variety of applications, including lithium-ion batteries, refractories, and foundries, among others.
[src:graphene-materials/graphite] Significant work has been done on graphitizing of traditionally non-graphitizable carbons.
[src:graphene-materials/graphite] A company in New Zealand utilizes forestry waste to produce what they have termed 'biographite' through a process referred to as thermo-catalytic graphitization.
[src:graphene-materials/graphite] Another group in the United States uses a method referred to as photocatalytic graphitization to produce highly crystalline highly pure graphite for lithium-ion batteries and other applications from a variety of carbon sources.
[src:graphene-materials/graphite] Graphite occurs in metamorphic rocks as a result of the reduction of sedimentary carbon compounds during metamorphism.
[src:graphene-materials/graphite] It also occurs in igneous rocks and in meteorites.
[src:graphene-materials/graphite] Minerals associated with graphite include quartz, calcite, micas and tourmaline.
[src:graphene-materials/graphite] The principal export sources of mined graphite are, in order of tonnage, China, Mexico, Canada, Brazil, and Madagascar.
[src:graphene-materials/graphite] Significant unexploited graphite resources also exist in Colombia's Cordillera Central in the form of graphite-bearing schists.
[src:graphene-materials/graphite] In meteorites, graphite occurs with troilite and silicate minerals.
[src:graphene-materials/graphite] Small graphitic crystals in meteoritic iron are called cliftonite.
[src:graphene-materials/graphite] Some microscopic grains have distinctive isotopic compositions, indicating that they were formed before the Solar System.
[src:graphene-materials/graphite] They are one of about 12 known types of minerals that predate the Solar System and have also been detected in molecular clouds.
[src:graphene-materials/graphite] These minerals were formed in the ejecta when supernovae exploded or low to intermediate-sized stars expelled their outer envelopes late in their lives.
[src:graphene-materials/graphite] Graphite may be the second or third oldest mineral in the Universe.
[src:graphene-materials/graphite] Graphite consists of sheets of trigonal planar carbon.
[src:graphene-materials/graphite] The individual layers are called graphene.
[src:graphene-materials/graphite] In each layer, each carbon atom is bonded to three other atoms forming a continuous layer of sp2 bonded carbon hexagons, like a honeycomb lattice with a bond length of 0.142 nm, and the distance between planes is 0.335 nm.
[src:graphene-materials/graphite] Bonding between layers is relatively weak van der Waals bonds, which allows the graphene-like layers to be easily separated and to glide past each other.
[src:graphene-materials/graphite] Electrical conductivity perpendicular to the layers is consequently about 1000 times lower.
[src:graphene-materials/graphite] There are two allotropic forms called *alpha* (hexagonal) and *beta* (rhombohedral), differing in terms of the stacking of the graphene layers: stacking in alpha graphite is ABA, as opposed to ABC stacking in the energetically less stable beta graphite.
[src:graphene-materials/graphite] Rhombohedral graphite cannot occur in pure form.
[src:graphene-materials/graphite] Natural graphite, or commercial natural graphite, contains 5 to 15% rhombohedral graphite and this may be due to intensive milling.
[src:graphene-materials/graphite] The alpha form can be converted to the beta form through shear forces, and the beta form reverts to the alpha form when it is heated to 1300 °C for four hours.
[src:graphene-materials/graphite] The equilibrium pressure and temperature conditions for a transition between graphite and diamond is well established theoretically and experimentally.
[src:graphene-materials/graphite] The pressure changes linearly between 1.7 GPa at 0 K and 12 GPa at 5000 K (the diamond/graphite/liquid triple point).
[src:graphene-materials/graphite] However, the phases have a wide region about this line where they can coexist.
[src:graphene-materials/graphite] At normal temperature and pressure, 20 °C (293 K) and 1 standard atmosphere (0.10 MPa), the stable phase of carbon is graphite, but diamond is metastable and its rate of conversion to graphite is negligible.
[src:graphene-materials/graphite] However, at temperatures above about 4500 K, diamond rapidly converts to graphite.
[src:graphene-materials/graphite] Rapid conversion of graphite to diamond requires pressures well above the equilibrium line: at 2000 K, a pressure of 35 GPa is needed.
[src:graphene-materials/graphite] The acoustic and thermal properties of graphite are highly anisotropic, since phonons propagate quickly along the tightly bound planes, but are slower to travel from one plane to another.
[src:graphene-materials/graphite] Graphite's high thermal stability and electrical and thermal conductivity facilitate its widespread use as electrodes and refractories in high temperature material processing applications.
[src:graphene-materials/graphite] However, in oxygen-containing atmospheres graphite readily oxidizes to form carbon dioxide at temperatures of 700 °C and above.
[src:graphene-materials/graphite] Graphite is an electrical conductor, hence useful in such applications as arc lamp electrodes.
[src:graphene-materials/graphite] It can conduct electricity due to the vast electron delocalization within the carbon layers (a phenomenon called aromaticity).
[src:graphene-materials/graphite] These valence electrons are free to move, so are able to conduct electricity.
[src:graphene-materials/graphite] However, the electricity is primarily conducted within the plane of the layers.
[src:graphene-materials/graphite] The conductive properties of powdered graphite allow its use as pressure sensor in carbon microphones.
[src:graphene-materials/graphite] Graphite and graphite powder are valued in industrial applications for their self-lubricating and dry lubricating properties.
[src:graphene-materials/graphite] However, the use of graphite is limited by its tendency to facilitate pitting corrosion in some stainless steel, and to promote galvanic corrosion between dissimilar metals (due to its electrical conductivity).
[src:graphene-materials/graphite] It is also corrosive to aluminium in the presence of moisture.
[src:graphene-materials/graphite] For this reason, the US Air Force banned its use as a lubricant in aluminium aircraft, and discouraged its use in aluminium-containing automatic weapons.
[src:graphene-materials/graphite] Even graphite pencil marks on aluminium parts may facilitate corrosion.
[src:graphene-materials/graphite] Another high-temperature lubricant, hexagonal boron nitride, has the same molecular structure as graphite.
[src:graphene-materials/graphite] It is sometimes called *white graphite*, due to its similar properties.
[src:graphene-materials/graphite] When a large number of crystallographic defects bind its planes together, graphite loses its lubrication properties and becomes what is known as pyrolytic graphite.
[src:graphene-materials/graphite] It is also highly anisotropic, and diamagnetic, thus it will float in mid-air above a strong magnet.
[src:graphene-materials/graphite] (If it is made in a fluidized bed at 1000–1300 °C then it is isotropic turbostratic, and is used in blood-contacting devices like mechanical heart valves and is called pyrolytic carbon, and is not diamagnetic.
[src:graphene-materials/graphite] For a long time graphite has been considered to be hydrophobic.
[src:graphene-materials/graphite] However, recent studies using highly ordered pyrolytic graphite have shown that freshly clean graphite is hydrophilic (contact angle of 70° approximately), and it becomes hydrophobic (contact angle of 95° approximately) due to airborne pollutants (hydrocarbons) present in the atmosphere.
[src:graphene-materials/graphite] Those contaminants also alter the electric equipotential surface of graphite by creating domains with potential differences of up to 200 mV as measured with kelvin probe force microscopy.
[src:graphene-materials/graphite] Such contaminants can be desorbed by increasing the temperature of graphite to approximately 50 °C or higher.
[src:graphene-materials/graphite] Natural and crystalline graphites are not often used in pure form as structural materials, due to their shear-planes, brittleness, and inconsistent mechanical properties.
[src:graphene-materials/graphite] In the 4th millennium BCE, during the Neolithic Age in southeastern Europe, the Marița culture used graphite in a ceramic paint for decorating pottery.
[src:graphene-materials/graphite] Sometime before 1565 (some sources say as early as 1500), an enormous deposit of graphite was discovered on the approach to Grey Knotts from the hamlet of Seathwaite in Borrowdale parish, Cumbria, England, which the locals found useful for marking sheep.
[src:graphene-materials/graphite] During the reign of Elizabeth I (1558–1603), Borrowdale graphite was used as a refractory material to line molds for cannonballs, resulting in rounder, smoother balls that could be fired farther, contributing to the strength of the English navy.
[src:graphene-materials/graphite] This particular deposit of graphite was extremely pure and soft, and could easily be cut into sticks.
[src:graphene-materials/graphite] Because of its military importance, this unique mine and its production were strictly controlled by the Crown.
[src:graphene-materials/graphite] During the 19th century, graphite's uses greatly expanded to include stove polish, lubricants, paints, crucibles, foundry facings, and pencils, a major factor in the expansion of educational tools during the first great rise of education for the masses.
[src:graphene-materials/graphite] The British Empire controlled most of the world's production (especially from Ceylon), but production from Austrian, German, and American deposits expanded by mid-century.
[src:graphene-materials/graphite] The Dixon pencil is still in production.
[src:graphene-materials/graphite] The beginnings of the revolutionary froth flotation process are associated with graphite mining.
[src:graphene-materials/graphite] Included in the *E&MJ* article on the Dixon Crucible Company is a sketch of the "floating tanks" used in the age-old process of extracting graphite.
[src:graphene-materials/graphite] Because graphite is so light, the mix of graphite and waste was sent through a final series of water tanks where a cleaner graphite "floated" off, which left waste to drop out.
[src:graphene-materials/graphite] Adolph Bessel received the Wohler Medal for the patented process that upgraded the recovery of graphite to 90% from the German deposit.
[src:graphene-materials/graphite] In 1977, the German Society of Mining Engineers and Metallurgists organized a special symposium dedicated to their discovery and, thus, the 100th anniversary of flotation.
[src:graphene-materials/graphite] In the United States, in 1885, Hezekiah Bradford of Philadelphia patented a similar process, but it is uncertain if his process was used successfully in the nearby graphite deposits of Chester County, Pennsylvania, a major producer by the 1890s.
[src:graphene-materials/graphite] The Bessel process was limited in use, primarily because of the abundant cleaner deposits found around the globe, which needed not much more than hand-sorting to gather the pure graphite.
[src:graphene-materials/graphite] 1900, is described in the Canadian Department of Mines report on graphite mines and mining when Canadian deposits began to become important producers of graphite.
[src:graphene-materials/graphite] Historically, graphite was called **black lead** or **plumbago**.
[src:graphene-materials/graphite] Plumbago was commonly used in its massive mineral form.
[src:graphene-materials/graphite] Both of these names arise from confusion with the similar-appearing lead ores, particularly galena.
[src:graphene-materials/graphite] The Latin word for lead, *plumbum*, gave its name to the English term for this grey metallic-sheened mineral and even to the leadworts or plumbagos, plants with flowers that resemble this colour.
[src:graphene-materials/graphite] The term *black lead* usually refers to a powdered or processed graphite, matte black in color.
[src:graphene-materials/graphite] Abraham Gottlob Werner coined the name *graphite* ("writing stone") in 1789.
[src:graphene-materials/graphite] He attempted to clear up the confusion between molybdena, plumbago and black lead after Carl Wilhelm Scheele in 1778 proved that these were at least three different minerals.
[src:graphene-materials/graphite] Scheele's analysis showed that the chemical compounds molybdenum sulfide (molybdenite), lead(II) sulfide (galena) and graphite were three different soft black minerals.
[src:graphene-materials/graphite] Natural graphite is mostly used for refractories, batteries, steelmaking, expanded graphite, brake linings, foundry facings, and lubricants.
[src:graphene-materials/graphite] The use of graphite as a refractory (heat-resistant) material began before 1900 with graphite crucibles used to hold molten metal; this is now a minor part of refractories.
[src:graphene-materials/graphite] In the mid-1980s, the carbon-magnesite brick became important, and a bit later the alumina-graphite shape.
[src:graphene-materials/graphite] As of 2017 the order of importance is: alumina-graphite shapes, carbon-magnesite brick, Monolithics (gunning and ramming mixes), and then crucibles.
[src:graphene-materials/graphite] Crucibles began using very large flake graphite, and carbon-magnesite bricks requiring not quite so large flake graphite; for these and others there is now much more flexibility in the size of flake required, and amorphous graphite is no longer restricted to low-end refractories.
[src:graphene-materials/graphite] Alumina-graphite shapes are used as continuous casting ware, such as nozzles and troughs, to convey the molten steel from ladle to Mold, and carbon magnesite bricks line steel converters and electric-arc furnaces to withstand extreme temperatures.
[src:graphene-materials/graphite] Graphite blocks are also used in parts of blast furnace linings where the high thermal conductivity of the graphite is critical to ensuring adequate cooling of the bottom and hearth of the furnace.
[src:graphene-materials/graphite] High-purity monolithics are often used as a continuous furnace lining instead of carbon-magnesite bricks.
[src:graphene-materials/graphite] The US and European refractories industry had a crisis in 2000–2003, with an indifferent market for steel and a declining refractory consumption per tonne of steel underlying firm buyouts and many plant closures.
[src:graphene-materials/graphite] Many of the plant closures resulted from the acquisition of Harbison-Walker Refractories by RHI AG and some plants had their equipment auctioned off.
[src:graphene-materials/graphite] Since much of the lost capacity was for carbon-magnesite brick, graphite consumption within the refractories area moved towards alumina-graphite shapes and Monolithics, and away from the brick.
[src:graphene-materials/graphite] The major source of carbon-magnesite brick is now China.
[src:graphene-materials/graphite] Almost all of the above refractories are used to make steel and account for 75% of refractory consumption; the rest is used by a variety of industries, such as cement.
[src:graphene-materials/graphite] According to the United States Geological Survey (USGS), US natural graphite consumption in refractories comprised 12,500 tonnes in 2010.
[src:graphene-materials/graphite] The use of graphite in batteries has increased since the 1970s.
[src:graphene-materials/graphite] Natural and synthetic graphite are used as an anode material to construct electrodes in major battery technologies.
[src:graphene-materials/graphite] Graphite is the "predominant anode material used today in lithium-ion batteries".
[src:graphene-materials/graphite] Electric-vehicle (EV) batteries contain four basic components: anode, cathode, electrolyte, and separator.
[src:graphene-materials/graphite] While there is much focus on the cathode materials—lithium, nickel, cobalt, manganese, etc., the anode material used in virtually all EV batteries is graphite.
[src:graphene-materials/graphite] The demand for batteries, primarily nickel–metal hydride and lithium-ion batteries, caused a growth in demand for graphite in the late 1980s and early 1990s – a growth driven by portable electronics, such as portable CD players and power tools.
[src:graphene-materials/graphite] Laptops, mobile phones, tablets, and smartphone products have increased the demand for batteries.
[src:graphene-materials/graphite] Electric-vehicle batteries are anticipated to increase graphite demand.
[src:graphene-materials/graphite] As an example, a lithium-ion battery in a fully electric Nissan Leaf contains nearly 40 kg of graphite.
[src:graphene-materials/graphite] Radioactive graphite removed from nuclear reactors has been investigated as a source of electricity for low-power applications.
[src:graphene-materials/graphite] This waste is rich in carbon-14, which emits electrons through beta decay, so it could potentially be used as the basis for a betavoltaic device.
[src:graphene-materials/graphite] This concept is known as the diamond battery.
[src:graphene-materials/graphite] Natural graphite in steelmaking mostly goes into raising the carbon content in molten steel; it can also serve to lubricate the dies used to extrude hot steel.
[src:graphene-materials/graphite] Carbon additives face competitive pricing from alternatives such as synthetic graphite powder, petroleum coke, and other forms of carbon.
[src:graphene-materials/graphite] A carbon raiser is added to increase the carbon content of the steel to a specified level.
[src:graphene-materials/graphite] An estimate based on USGS's graphite consumption statistics indicates that steelmakers in the US used 10,500 tonnes in this fashion in 2005.
[src:graphene-materials/graphite] Natural amorphous and fine flake graphite are used in brake linings or brake shoes for heavier (nonautomotive) vehicles, and became important with the need to substitute for asbestos.
[src:graphene-materials/graphite] This use has been important for quite some time, but nonasbestos organic (NAO) compositions are beginning to reduce graphite's market share.
[src:graphene-materials/graphite] A brake-lining industry shake-out with some plant closures has not been beneficial, nor has an indifferent automotive market.
[src:graphene-materials/graphite] According to the USGS, US natural graphite consumption in brake linings was 6,510 tonnes in 2005.
[src:graphene-materials/graphite] A foundry-facing mold wash is a water-based paint of amorphous or fine flake graphite.
[src:graphene-materials/graphite] Painting the inside of a mold with it and letting it dry leaves a fine graphite coat that will ease the separation of the object cast after the hot metal has cooled.
[src:graphene-materials/graphite] Graphite lubricants are specialty items for use at very high or very low temperatures, as forging die lubricant, an antiseize agent, a gear lubricant for mining machinery, and to lubricate locks.
[src:graphene-materials/graphite] Having low-grit graphite, or even better, no-grit graphite (ultra high purity), is highly desirable.
[src:graphene-materials/graphite] It can be used as a dry powder, in water or oil, or as colloidal graphite (a permanent suspension in a liquid).
[src:graphene-materials/graphite] An estimate based on USGS graphite consumption statistics indicates that 2,200 tonnes were used in this fashion in 2005.
[src:graphene-materials/graphite] Metal can also be impregnated into graphite to create a self-lubricating alloy for application in extreme conditions, such as bearings for machines exposed to high or low temperatures.
[src:graphene-materials/graphite] The ability to leave marks on paper and other objects gave graphite its name, given in 1789 by German mineralogist Abraham Gottlob Werner.
[src:graphene-materials/graphite] It stems from *γράφειν ("graphein")*, meaning *to write* or *draw* in Ancient Greek.
[src:graphene-materials/graphite] From the 16th century, all pencils were made with leads of English natural graphite, but modern pencil lead is most commonly a mix of powdered graphite and clay; it was invented by Nicolas-Jacques Conté in 1795.
[src:graphene-materials/graphite] It is chemically unrelated to the metal lead, whose ores had a similar appearance, hence the continuation of the name.
[src:graphene-materials/graphite] **Plumbago** is another older term for natural graphite used for drawing, typically as a lump of the mineral without a wood casing.
[src:graphene-materials/graphite] The term plumbago drawing is normally restricted to 17th and 18th-century works, mostly portraits.
[src:graphene-materials/graphite] Today, pencils are still a small but significant market for natural graphite.
[src:graphene-materials/graphite] Around 7% of the 1.1 million tonnes produced in 2011 was used to make pencils.
[src:graphene-materials/graphite] Low-quality amorphous graphite is used and sourced mainly from China.
[src:graphene-materials/graphite] In art, graphite is typically used to create detailed and precise drawings, as it allows for a wide range of values (light to dark) to be achieved.
[src:graphene-materials/graphite] It can also be used to create softer, more subtle lines and shading.
[src:graphene-materials/graphite] Graphite is popular among artists because it is easy to control, easy to erase, and produces a clean, professional look.
[src:graphene-materials/graphite] It is also relatively inexpensive and widely available.
[src:graphene-materials/graphite] Many artists use graphite in conjunction with other media, such as charcoal or ink, to create a range of effects and textures in their work.
[src:graphene-materials/graphite] Graphite of various hardness or softness results in different qualities and tones when used as an artistic medium.
[src:graphene-materials/graphite] Graphite is probably the most-used lubricant in pinewood derbies.
[src:graphene-materials/graphite] Natural graphite has found uses in zinc-carbon batteries, electric motor brushes, and various specialized applications.
[src:graphene-materials/graphite] Railroads would often mix powdered graphite with waste oil or linseed oil to create a heat-resistant protective coating for the exposed portions of a steam locomotive's boiler, such as the smokebox or lower part of the firebox.
[src:graphene-materials/graphite] The Scope soldering iron uses a graphite tip as its heating element.
[src:graphene-materials/graphite] Expanded graphite is made by immersing natural flake graphite in a bath of chromic acid, then concentrated sulfuric acid, which forces the crystal lattice planes apart, thus expanding the graphite.
[src:graphene-materials/graphite] After being made into graphite foil, the foil is machined and assembled into the bipolar plates in fuel cells.
[src:graphene-materials/graphite] The foil is made into heat sinks for laptop computers which keeps them cool while saving weight, and is made into a foil laminate that can be used in valve packings or made into gaskets.
[src:graphene-materials/graphite] Old-style packings are now a minor member of this grouping: fine flake graphite in oils or greases for uses requiring heat resistance.
[src:graphene-materials/graphite] A GAN estimate of current US natural graphite consumption in this end-use is 7,500 tonnes.
[src:graphene-materials/graphite] Graphite forms intercalation compounds with some metals and small molecules.
[src:graphene-materials/graphite] In these compounds, the host molecule or atom gets "sandwiched" between the graphite layers, resulting in a type of compound with variable stoichiometry.
[src:graphene-materials/graphite] A prominent example of an intercalation compound is potassium graphite, denoted by the formula KC8.
